{"title_page": "Paterson Clarence Hughes", "text_new": "{{short description|Royal Australian Air Force fighter pilot}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Paterson Clarence Hughes\n|birth_date=19 September 1917\n|death_date={{death date and age|1940|9|7|1917|9|19|df=yes}}\n|birth_place=[[Cooma, New South Wales|Cooma]], New South Wales, Australia\n|death_place=[[Sundridge, Kent|Sundridge]], Kent, England\n|image= Paterson Clarence Hughes 1940.jpg\n|alt=Portrait of man in dark military uniform with pilot's wings\n|caption=Pat Hughes, 1940\n|nickname=\n|allegiance=Australia<br/>United Kingdom\n|branch=[[Royal Australian Air Force]] (1936\u201337)<br/>[[Royal Air Force]] (1937\u201340)\n|serviceyears=1936\u201340\n|servicenumber=39461 (RAF)<ref name=DFC>{{London Gazette|issue=34976 |page=6134|date= 22 October 1940}}</ref>\n|rank=[[Flight Lieutenant]]\n|unit= [[No. 64 Squadron RAF]] (1937\u201339)<br />[[No. 234 Squadron RAF]] (1939\u201340)\n|battles=World War II\n* [[European air campaign (World War II)|European air campaign]]\n** [[Battle of Britain]] {{KIA}}\n|awards=[[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]]\n}}\n'''Paterson Clarence Hughes''', [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]] (19 September 1917&nbsp;\u2013 7&nbsp;September 1940) was an Australian [[flying ace|fighter ace]] of World War&nbsp;II. Serving with the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF), he was credited with as many as seventeen aerial victories during the [[Battle of Britain]], before being killed in action on 7&nbsp;September 1940. His tally made him the highest-scoring Australian of the battle, and among the three highest-scoring Australians of the war.\n\nBorn in [[Cooma, New South Wales|Cooma]], New South Wales, Hughes joined the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] as a cadet in 1936. After graduating as a pilot,  he chose to take a commission with the RAF. In July 1937, he was assigned to [[No. 64 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;64 Squadron]], which operated [[Hawker Demon]] and, later, [[Bristol Blenheim]] fighters. Posted to [[No. 234 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;234 Squadron]] following the outbreak of World War&nbsp;II, Hughes began flying [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s as a [[flight commander]]. He shared in his unit's first aerial victory on 8&nbsp;July 1940, and began scoring heavily against the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' the following month. Known for his practice of attacking his targets at extremely close range, Hughes is generally thought to have died after his Spitfire was struck by flying debris from a German bomber that he had just shot down. He was posthumously awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]], and was buried in England.\n\n==Early life==\nPaterson Clarence Hughes was born in Numeralla, near [[Cooma, New South Wales|Cooma]], New South Wales, on 19&nbsp;September 1917. He was the second-youngest of twelve children, the last of four boys in his family.<ref name=ADB>{{cite web|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/hughes-paterson-clarence-10564 |title= Hughes, Paterson Clarence (1917\u20131940)|last=Newton|first=Dennis|work= [[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]|accessdate= 26 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=Alexander30>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 30\u201331</ref> Hughes' father was a teacher by profession but at the time of Pat's birth was running the community post office; christened Percival Clarence Hughes, and known as Percy, he had apparently adopted the name Paterson by the time of his marriage to Catherine Vennell in 1895. Percy was also a writer, contributing to newspapers and magazines such as ''[[The Bulletin (Australian periodical)|The Bulletin]]'', and \"Paterson\" may have been homage to the poet [[Banjo Paterson]]. In any case, Pat shared his father's interest in literature. He also grew to love the landscape of the local [[Monaro (New South Wales)|Monaro district]] in the shadow of the [[Snowy Mountains]], which he described as \"unrivalled in the magnificence and grandeur of its beauty\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 28\u201330</ref>\n\n[[File:Paterson Clarence Hughes 1936 (AWM P00835.001).JPG|thumb|left|upright|Hughes, c. December 1936|alt=Studio portrait of young man wearing dark military uniform with pilot's wings and peaked cap]]\nHughes was educated at Cooma Public School until the age of twelve, when the family moved to [[Haberfield, New South Wales|Haberfield]] in [[Sydney]]; his father was by then working as a labourer.<ref name=Alexander30/><ref name=Newton>Newton, ''Australian Air Aces'', pp. 91\u201392</ref> He attended [[Petersham, New South Wales|Petersham Boys' School]], becoming a [[school prefect|prefect]] in 1932 and vice captain the following year.<ref name=Alexander30/> As well as playing sport, he was a keen aircraft modeller and built [[crystal radio]] sets.<ref name=Claason141>Claasen, ''Dogfight'', p. 141</ref> Having attained his [[Intermediate Certificate (Australia)|intermediate certificate]], Hughes entered [[Fort Street High School]] in February 1934.<ref name=Alexander30/> He left after eight months to take up employment at Saunders' Jewellers in [[George Street, Sydney]], and enlisted in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] (RAAF) on 20&nbsp;January 1936.<ref name=Alexander30/><ref name=Garrisson>Garrisson, ''Australian Fighter Aces'', p. 140</ref> Hughes had also applied to, and been accepted by, the [[Royal Australian Navy]], but chose the RAAF.<ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 8</ref>\n\nTraining as an air cadet at [[RAAF Williams#RAAF Williams Point Cook Base|RAAF Point Cook]] near [[Melbourne]], Hughes learnt to fly in [[de Havilland Moth]]s before progressing to [[Westland Wapiti]]s in the middle of the year.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 40, 46</ref> A practical joker who bridled under RAAF discipline, his euphoria during his first solo on 11&nbsp;March 1936 was such that he \"went mad, whistled, sang and almost jumped for joy\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 42, 45</ref> A fellow cadet recalled that Hughes \"loved life and lived it at high pressure\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 36</ref> Upon graduation in December 1936, Hughes was assessed as having \"no outstanding qualities\" despite being \"energetic and keen\".<ref name=Garrisson/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 48</ref> Under a pre-war arrangement between the British and Australian governments, he volunteered for transfer to the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF), and sailed for the United Kingdom in January 1937.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Stephens>Stephens, ''The Royal Australian Air Force'', pp. 84\u201385</ref> His decision to transfer had not been quick or easy; though keen to \"try and do something special\" in England, and intrigued by \"a fascinating picture of easy life, beer and women\" that had been presented to him, in the end he felt that it was simply \"willed\" that he should go.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 47</ref>\n\n==Early RAF service==\nOn 20&nbsp;March 1937, Hughes was granted a five-year short-service commission as a [[pilot officer]] in the RAF.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34376|page=1417|date=20 March 1937}}</ref>  Like some of his compatriots, he refused to exchange his dark-blue RAAF uniform for the lighter-coloured RAF one.<ref name=Claason141/> He undertook advanced flying instruction at [[No. 2 Flying Training School RAF|No.&nbsp;2 Flying Training School]] in [[Digby, Lincolnshire|Digby]], Lincolnshire. Slated to fly bombers, he appealed and in July was posted as a fighter pilot to [[No. 64 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;64 Squadron]], which operated [[Hawker Demon]]s out of [[RAF Martlesham Heath]], Suffolk.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 51\u201352</ref> The squadron was transferred to [[RAF Church Fenton]], Yorkshire, in May 1938.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 54\u201355</ref> Hughes was promoted to [[flying officer]] on 19&nbsp;November.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34577|page=7695|date= 19 November 1938}}</ref> No.&nbsp;64 Squadron subsequently received [[Bristol Blenheim|Bristol Blenheim&nbsp;1F]] twin-engined fighters, and completed its conversion to the type in January 1939.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 64</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n|quote  = There's no use muttering about things... to my mind the chances of living through this are about equal anyhow, and that's all one can ask after all...\n|source = \u2014Hughes to his brother shortly after the outbreak of World War II <ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', pp. 6\u20137</ref>\n|align  = right\n|width  = 31%\n}}\nHughes was promoted to acting [[flight lieutenant]] in November 1939 and became a [[flight commander]] in the newly formed [[No. 234 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;234 Squadron]], which, like No.&nbsp;64 Squadron, came under the control of [[No. 13 Group RAF|No.&nbsp;13 Group]] in the north of England.<ref name=ADB/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. viii, 90, 127</ref> On establishment the previous month at [[RAF Leconfield]], East Yorkshire, No.&nbsp;234 Squadron was equipped with Blenheims, [[Fairey Battle]]s and [[Gloster Gauntlet]]s; it began re-arming with [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s in March 1940 and was operational two months later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/234squadron.cfm|title=234 Squadron|publisher=[[Royal Air Force]]|accessdate=26 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704024902/http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/234squadron.cfm|archivedate=4 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The commanding officer, [[Squadron Leader]] Richard Barnett, rarely flew, and Hughes assumed responsibility for overseeing conversion to the Spitfire.<ref name=Bungay1>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', pp. 1\u20132</ref><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 126, 398</ref> \"More experienced and more mature\" than his fellow pilots, according to historian [[Stephen Bungay]], the Australian \"effectively led\" No.&nbsp;234 Squadron.<ref>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 172</ref> By this time, Hughes had acquired a young [[Airedale Terrier]] known as Flying Officer Butch, who sometimes flew with him\u2014against regulations. He had also met and begun dating Kathleen (\"Kay\") Brodrick of [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]].<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 121\u2013123</ref> On 19&nbsp;June, Hughes and his squadron transferred to [[RAF St&nbsp;Eval]], Cornwall, under the jurisdiction of the newly formed [[No. 10 Group RAF|No.&nbsp;10 Group]] in south-west England.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. viii, xii, 153</ref>\n\n==Battle of Britain==\nAs the [[Battle of Britain]] got under way in July 1940, Hughes shared in No.&nbsp;234 Squadron's first confirmed aerial victories.<ref name=ADB/><ref>Garrisson, ''Australian Fighter Aces'', p. 35</ref> He and his section of two other Spitfires shot down a German [[Junkers Ju&nbsp;88]] attacking convoys near [[Lands End]] on 8&nbsp;July, and another south-east of [[Plymouth]] during a dawn patrol on 28&nbsp;July.<ref name=Newton/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 162, 179</ref> A shared claim for a Ju&nbsp;88 on 27&nbsp;July could not be confirmed as destroyed; after a chase over the water at heights as low as {{convert|50|feet|m}}, the German escaped, despite being struck in the engines and cockpit, and was credited to the section as \"damaged\".<ref name=Few178>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 178\u2013179</ref><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', pp. 64\u201365</ref> German records, made available post-war, confirm that a Junkers 88A, piloted by Leutnant Ruckdeschel, was lost on this day.<ref>Mason, ''Battle Over Britain'', p.153</ref> On 1&nbsp;August, Hughes was seconded from No.&nbsp;234 Squadron to help set up the only [[Gloster Gladiator]]-equipped unit to operate during the Battle of Britain, [[No. 247 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;247 (China British) Squadron]] in Plymouth.<ref name=ADB/><ref>Shores; Williams, ''Aces High'', p. 48</ref> The same day, he married Kay Brodrick, who likened him to [[Errol Flynn]], in the [[register office]] at [[Bodmin]], Cornwall.<ref name=ADB/><ref name=Bungay310>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 310</ref> Apart from Flying Officer Butch, the witnesses were strangers; Kay arrived alone, and no-one from No.&nbsp;234 Squadron could attend.<ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 72</ref><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 180</ref> Barnett was transferred out of No.&nbsp;234 Squadron on 13&nbsp;August, and Hughes took temporary command until the arrival of Squadron Leader Joe \"Spike\" O'Brien four days later.<ref name=Bungay1/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 198, 210</ref> By now the fighting was intensifying over southern England, and the squadron relocated from St&nbsp;Eval to [[RAF Middle Wallop]], Hampshire, on 14&nbsp;August.<ref name=Bungay1/><ref name=Price66>Price, ''Spitfire Mk.I/II Aces'', p. 66</ref> Almost immediately after Hughes landed the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' bombed the airfield; several ground staff and civilian workers were killed, but No.&nbsp;234 Squadron's Spitfires escaped damage.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 199</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n|quote  = No-one had more air sense than Pat&nbsp;... his only problem was that he got too close but that was his way.\n|source = \u2014Joe Roddis, Hughes' [[Fitter (occupation)|fitter]] <ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 263, 344</ref>\n|align  = right\n|width  = 31%\n}}\nIt was following No.&nbsp;234 Squadron's move to Middle Wallop that Hughes began to score heavily against German fighters.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Price66/> On 15&nbsp;August, in one of the costliest engagements of the Battle of Britain, known thereafter to the ''Luftwaffe'' as \"Black Thursday\", Hughes claimed victories (one of them shared) over two [[Messerschmitt Bf 110]]s.<ref name=Newton/><ref>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 218</ref>  He again achieved dual success on 16, 18 and 26&nbsp;August, all six victims being [[Messerschmitt Bf&nbsp;109]]s brought down in the vicinity of the [[Isle of Wight]].<ref name=Newton/> Whereas in July he had fired at his targets from a range of {{convert|150|to|50|yd}}, it was now his habit to close to {{convert|30|yd}}, approximately three Spitfire lengths, before delivering his final burst; he also made head-on attacks against enemy aircraft.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 215</ref>  He had a narrow escape on the 16th after his second victory of the day, when he chased a quartet of [[Junkers Ju&nbsp;87]]s and had his [[tailplane]] shot up from behind by another Bf&nbsp;109; he dived and forced the German to overshoot, then broke off having exhausted his ammunition firing at his former attacker. In the pub with Kay and his squadron mates that evening, Hughes jokingly told his wife, \"In case of accidents make sure you marry again\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 207\u2013210</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1969-094-18, Dornier Do 17 und Supermarine Spitfire.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.28|Dornier Do 17 and Supermarine Spitfire, 1940|alt=Twin-engined, twin-finned aircraft in flight with single-engined aircraft in lower background]]\nOn 3&nbsp;September, Hughes' promotion to [[substantive rank|substantive]] flight lieutenant was promulgated in ''[[The London Gazette]]''.<ref name=ADB/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34954|page=5715|date= 3 September 1940}}</ref> He claimed three Me&nbsp;110s in the space of fifteen minutes south of [[Haslemere]] on 4&nbsp;September, two Bf&nbsp;109s while patrolling [[Kenley]] the following day, and a Bf&nbsp;109 destroyed plus one probable near [[Dover]] on 6&nbsp;September; he had to break off combat with the last-mentioned when its tanks ruptured, covering Hughes' canopy in oil.<ref name=Newton/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 247\u2013250</ref> One of his victims on 5&nbsp;September may have been Oberleutnant [[Franz von Werra]], who was captured and subsequently became famous as \"[[the One That Got Away (1957 film)|the one that got away]]\".<ref name=ADB/><ref>Claasen, ''Dogfight'', pp. 142\u2013143</ref> Hughes and his prot\u00e9g\u00e9, [[Bob Doe]], claimed half of No.&nbsp;234 Squadron's victories between mid-August and early September.<ref>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', pp. 172, 196</ref>\n\nHughes was killed in action on the evening of 7&nbsp;September 1940, after he intercepted a [[Dornier Do&nbsp;17]] bomber taking part in a large-scale attack on London.<ref name=ADB/><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', pp. 166\u2013167</ref> His Spitfire crashed in a field between [[Sundridge, Kent|Sundridge]] and [[Bessels Green]] in [[Kent]]. He apparently bailed out, but his parachute failed to open; his body was found in a garden on Main Road, Sundridge, not far from the wreck of his Spitfire. The Dornier came down in the [[River Darent]].<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 260\u2013261, 343</ref> No.&nbsp;234 Squadron lost its commanding officer, O'Brien, in the same action.<ref name=Bungay310/><ref name=Bishop>Bishop, ''Battle of Britain'', p. 305</ref> Mystery surrounds exactly how Hughes came to grief, though his close-in tactics are believed to have played a major part in it.<ref name=Newton/> The strain of regular combat without respite, manifesting itself in fatigue and spots before the eyes, may also have contributed.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 250\u2013254, 259\u2013260</ref><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 161</ref> He is generally thought to have collided with flying wreckage from the crippled German bomber, rendering his Spitfire uncontrollable.<ref name=Garrisson/><ref name=Bishop/><ref>Wilson, ''The Brotherhood of Airmen'', p. 67</ref> It is also possible that Hughes accidentally rammed his target. Further speculation suggested that he was the victim of [[friendly fire]] from another British fighter attacking the same Dornier, or was struck by German bullets from a Bf&nbsp;109.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Bungay472>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 472</ref> Some observers on the ground, including [[Coal mining|collier]] Charles Hall, maintained that Hughes rammed the Dornier on purpose.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 261</ref> Four days after his death, No.&nbsp;234 Squadron was moved back to the relative quiet of Cornwall.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Alexander265>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 265</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{Quote box\n|quote  = Everyone talks about the wrong people&nbsp;... the self-publicists. Now who has ever heard of Pat Hughes? He saved our squadron, and he shot down a lot more than others I could name. But he died you see. That was a blow.\n|source = \u2014Bob Doe, quoted in 2000 <ref>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 400</ref>\n|align  = right\n|width  = 31%\n}}\nThe top-scoring Australian [[flying ace]] of the Battle of Britain and one of fourteen Australian fighter pilots killed during the battle,<ref name=Garrisson/><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 1</ref> Hughes has been described as \"the inspiration and driving force behind No.&nbsp;234 Squadron RAF\".<ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 167</ref> He is generally credited with seventeen confirmed victories\u2014fourteen solo and three shared.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Price66/> This tally puts him among the top ten [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] Battle of Britain aces.<ref name=Alexander263>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 263</ref><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 283</ref> It also ranks him among the three highest-scoring Australians of World War&nbsp;II, after [[Clive Caldwell]] with thirty victories (twenty-seven solo and three shared) and [[Adrian Goldsmith]] with seventeen (sixteen solo and one shared).<ref name=Alexander263/><ref>Newton, ''Australian Air Aces'', pp. 117\u2013118</ref>\n\nA war widow after barely five weeks of marriage, Kay Hughes was inconsolable in her loss: \"I wept until I could cry no more\".<ref name=Alexander265/> Flying Officer Butch ran out of the [[mess]] on the day of his master's death, and was never seen again.<ref name=Alexander264>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 264\u2013265</ref> Following a service at St James', [[Sutton-on-Hull]], on 13&nbsp;September 1940, Hughes was buried in the churchyard at Row&nbsp;G, Grave&nbsp;4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2414101/HUGHES,%20PATERSON%20CLARENCE|title=Hughes, Paterson Clarence|publisher=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> A week later, Kay discovered she was pregnant, but eventually miscarried.<ref name=Alexander265/> She subsequently drove ambulances for the British war effort.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 335</ref> News of his son's marriage came as \"a complete surprise\" to Percy Hughes, who only learned of his daughter-in-law's existence from the Australian Air Board's casualty letter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://recordsearch.naa.gov.au/SearchNRetrieve/Interface/ViewImage.aspx?B=1054979&S=1|title= Hughes, Paterson Clarence&nbsp;\u2013 Casualty File|publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]]|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> Having married three more times after Hughes' death, Kay died on 28&nbsp;June 1983 and, in accordance with her wishes, her ashes were buried with her first husband, whose headstone was amended to read \"In loving memory of his wife Kathleen\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 335\u2013336</ref>\n\nHughes was posthumously awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (DFC) on 22&nbsp;October 1940 for his \"skill and determination\" as a flight commander and \"gallantry in his attacks on the enemy\"; Squadron Leader O'Brien had recommended the decoration a week before their deaths.<ref name=DFC/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 264</ref> Kay was presented with the medal at [[Buckingham Palace]] on 23&nbsp;June 1942.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47337212 |title=Late Sydney pilot |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=24 June 1942 |accessdate=16 June 2015 |page=2}}</ref> In Australia, Hughes is commemorated at Christ's Church, [[Kiama]], with a memorial tablet placed by his sister Muriel.<ref name=ADB/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warmemorialsregister.nsw.gov.au/content/paterson-clarence-hughes-memorial-tablet|title=Paterson Clarence Hughes Memorial Tablet|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales Government]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref>  A special memorial is dedicated to him at Monaghan Hayes Place, Cooma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cooma.nsw.gov.au/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=914:monaghan-hayes-place&catid=202&Itemid=103|title=Flight Lieutenant Paterson Clarence Hughes DFC Memorial|publisher=[[Cooma-Monaro Shire|Cooma\u2013Monaro Shire Council]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> His name appears on the [[Battle of Britain Roll of Honour]] in [[Westminster Abbey]], and on supplementary panel&nbsp;12 in the Commemorative Area of the [[Australian War Memorial]] (AWM), [[Canberra]].<ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', pp. 267\u2013268</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.awm.gov.au/research/people/roll_of_honour/person/R1719963/|title=Roll of Honour&nbsp;\u2013 Paterson Clarence Hughes|publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> The AWM also holds his DFC and service medals in its collection.<ref name=AWM>{{cite  web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/collection/REL/17986.001 |title= Distinguished Flying Cross: Flight Lieutenant P.C. Hughes, 234 Squadron RAF|publisher=Australian War Memorial|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> Kay had given the medals to her sisters-in-law to pass on to Percy in the 1950s and, after being lost during an [[Anzac Day]] parade in the 1960s, they went through several family members' hands before turning up in the safe of the Kiama [[Country Women's Association]]; they were donated to the AWM in 1990.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 341\u2013343</ref> On 7&nbsp;September 2005, Charles Hall's sons dedicated a plaque in Hughes' honour at the house where he fell in Main Road, Sundridge; Bob Doe attended, expressing his thanks for \"an Australian who came to help us when we needed him\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 343</ref> [[Shoreham Aircraft Museum]] in Kent unveiled a memorial stone to Hughes at Sundridge on 23&nbsp;August 2008.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 344</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shoreham-aircraft-museum.co.uk/memorials-hughes.htm|title= Local Memorials Project: Flight Lieutenant Pat Hughes|publisher=[[Shoreham Aircraft Museum]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> On 15&nbsp;September 2014, the AWM's daily [[Last Post|Last Post Ceremony]] was dedicated to Hughes' memory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/PAFU2014/343.01/|title=The Last Post Ceremony commemorating the service of Flight Lieutenant Paterson Clarence Hughes DFC, No. 234 Squadron, RAF, Second World War|publisher=Australian War Memorial|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Combat record==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=\"40\" align=center|No.\n!width=\"140\" align=center|Date\n!width=\"70\" align=center|Flying\n!width=\"180\" align=center|Foe\n!width=\"180\" align=center|Result\n!width=\"180\" align=center|Location\n|-\n|1\n|8 July 1940\n|[[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]]\n|[[Junkers Ju 88]]\n|Destroyed (shared) <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186>Shores; Williams, ''Aces High'', p. 186</ref>\n|SE [[Lands End]]\n|-\n|\u2013\n|27 July 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Junkers Ju 88\n|Damaged (shared) <ref name=Few178/><ref>Unconfirmed destroyed according to Newton, ''Australian Air Aces'', p. 92</ref>\n|SE Lands End\n|-\n|2\n|28 July 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Junkers Ju 88\n|Destroyed (shared) <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|SE [[Plymouth]]\n|-\n|3\n|15 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|[[Messerschmitt Bf 110]]\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Few204>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 204\u2013206</ref>\n|[[Middle Wallop]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Isle of Wight]]\n|-\n|4\n|15 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt  Bf 110\n|Destroyed (shared) <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Few204/>\n|SW [[Swanage]]\n|-\n|5\n|16 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|[[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|6\n|16 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|7\n|18 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|8\n|18 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|9\n|26 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|10\n|26 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|11\n|4 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 110\n|Destroyed <ref name=Shores186/><ref name=Newton91>Newton, ''Australian Air Aces'', p. 91</ref>\n|[[Haslemere]]\u2013[[Brighton]]\n|-\n|12\n|4 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 110\n|Destroyed <ref name=Shores186/><ref name=Newton91/>\n|Haslemere\u2013Brighton\n|-\n|13\n|4 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 110\n|Destroyed <ref name=Shores186/><ref name=Newton91/>\n|Haslemere\u2013Brighton\n|-\n|14\n|5 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|[[Eastchurch]]\n|-\n|15\n|5 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|S [[Manston, Kent|Manston]]\n|-\n|16\n|6 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|[[Dover]]\n|-\n|\u2013\n|6 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Probable <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Dover\n|-\n|17\n|7 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|[[Dornier Do 17]]\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|London\u2013Brighton\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Alexander|first=Kristen|title=Australia's Few and the Battle of Britain|publisher=NewSouth Publishing|location=Sydney|year=2014|isbn=978-1-74224-694-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bishop|first=Patrick|title=Battle of Britain: A Day-by-Day Chronicle|publisher=[[Quercus (publisher)|Quercus Publishing]]|location=London|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84724-984-5|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/battleofbritaind0000bish}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bungay| first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Bungay|year=2000| title=The Most Dangerous Enemy: A History of the Battle of Britain | location=London| publisher= Aurom Press |isbn=978-1-85410-801-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Claasen| first=Adam|year=2004| title=Dogfight: The Battle of Britain | location=Auckland| publisher= Exisle Publishing |isbn=978-1-921497-28-5}}\n* {{cite book|last=Garrisson|first=A.D.|title=Australian Fighter Aces 1914\u20131953 |url=http://airpower.airforce.gov.au/Publications/Details/220/Australian-Fighter-Aces-1914\u20131953.aspx|publisher=Air Power Studies Centre|location=Fairbairn, Australian Capital Territory|year=1999|isbn=978-0-642-26540-1}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mason |first=Francis K. |title=Battle Over Britain |publisher=Aston |location=Bourne End |year=1990 |isbn=0-946627-15-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Newton |first=Dennis|year=1990 |title=A Few of 'the Few': Australians and the Battle of Britain|location=Canberra |publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]] |isbn=978-0-642-14991-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Newton| first=Dennis|year=1996| title=Australian Air Aces| location=Fyshwyck, Australian Capital Territory| publisher=Aerospace Publications|isbn=978-1-875671-25-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Price|first=Alfred|title=Spitfire Mk.I/II Aces 1939\u201341|year=1996|publisher=[[Osprey Publishing|Osprey]] |location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-85532-627-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shores| first=Christopher| last2=Williams|first2= Clive|year=1966| title=Aces High: The Fighter Aces of the British and Commonwealth Air Forces in World War II |location=London|publisher= Neville Spearman |isbn=|oclc=8013035}}\n* {{cite book|last=Stephens| first=Alan|origyear=2001|year=2006| title=The Royal Australian Air Force: A History|location=London| publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-555541-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wilson| first=David|year=2005| title=The Brotherhood of Airmen| location=Crows Nest, New South Wales| publisher=[[Allen & Unwin]] |isbn=1-74114-333-0}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://recordsearch.naa.gov.au/SearchNRetrieve/Interface/ViewImage.aspx?B=5250414&S=1 National Archives of Australia: Personal File]\n*[http://www.suttonandwawnemuseum.org.uk/pch.htm Sutton & Wawne Museum: A brief biography of the Australian fighter pilot killed during the Battle of Britain, and buried in Sutton churchyard in 1940]\n*[http://www.battleofbritain1940.net/0037.html Battle of Britain Historical Society: Saturday, September 7th 1940]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hughes, Pat}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Australian World War II flying aces]]\n[[Category:People from Cooma, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Royal Australian Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:The Few]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force pilots of World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Royal Australian Air Force fighter pilot}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Paterson Clarence Hughes\n|birth_date=19 September 1917\n|death_date={{death date and age|1940|9|7|1917|9|19|df=yes}}\n|birth_place=[[Cooma, New South Wales|Cooma]], New South Wales, Australia\n|death_place=[[Sundridge, Kent|Sundridge]], Kent, England\n|image= Paterson Clarence Hughes 1940.jpg\n|alt=Portrait of man in dark military uniform with pilot's wings\n|caption=Pat Hughes, 1940\n|nickname=\n|allegiance=Australia<br/>United Kingdom\n|branch=[[Royal Australian Air Force]] (1936\u201337)<br/>[[Royal Air Force]] (1937\u201340)\n|serviceyears=1936\u201340\n|servicenumber=39461 (RAF)<ref name=DFC>{{London Gazette|issue=34976 |page=6134|date= 22 October 1940}}</ref>\n|rank=[[Flight Lieutenant]]\n|unit= [[No. 64 Squadron RAF]] (1937\u201339)<br />[[No. 234 Squadron RAF]] (1939\u201340)\n|battles=World War II\n* [[European air campaign (World War II)|European air campaign]]\n** [[Battle of Britain]] {{KIA}}\n|awards=[[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]]\n}}\n'''Paterson Clarence Hughes''', [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]] (19 September 1917&nbsp;\u2013 7&nbsp;September 1940) was an Australian [[flying ace|fighter ace]] of World War&nbsp;II. Serving with the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF), he was credited with as many as seventeen aerial victories during the [[Battle of Britain]], before being killed in action on 7&nbsp;September 1940. His tally made him the highest-scoring Australian of the battle, and among the three highest-scoring Australians of the war.\n\nBorn in [[Cooma, New South Wales|Cooma]], New South Wales, Hughes joined the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] as a cadet in 1936. After graduating as a pilot,  he chose to take a commission with the RAF. In July 1937, he was assigned to [[No. 64 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;64 Squadron]], which operated [[Hawker Demon]] and, later, [[Bristol Blenheim]] fighters. Posted to [[No. 234 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;234 Squadron]] following the outbreak of World War&nbsp;II, Hughes began flying [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s as a [[flight commander]]. He shared in his unit's first aerial victory on 8&nbsp;July 1940, and began scoring heavily against the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' the following month. Known for his practice of attacking his targets at extremely close range, Hughes is generally thought to have died after his Spitfire was struck by flying debris from a German bomber that he had just shot down. He was posthumously awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]], and was buried in England.\n\n==Early life==\nPaterson Clarence Hughes was born in Numeralla, near [[Cooma, New South Wales|Cooma]], New South Wales, on 19&nbsp;September 1917. He was the second-youngest of twelve children, the last of four boys in his family.<ref name=ADB>{{cite web|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/hughes-paterson-clarence-10564 |title= Hughes, Paterson Clarence (1917\u20131940)|last=Newton|first=Dennis|work= [[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]|accessdate= 26 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=Alexander30>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 30\u201331</ref> Hughes' father was a teacher by profession but at the time of Pat's birth was running the community post office; christened Percival Clarence Hughes, and known as Percy, he had apparently adopted the name Paterson by the time of his marriage to Catherine Vennell in 1895. Percy was also a writer, contributing to newspapers and magazines such as ''[[The Bulletin (Australian periodical)|The Bulletin]]'', and \"Paterson\" may have been homage to the poet [[Banjo Paterson]]. In any case, Pat shared his father's interest in literature. He also grew to love the landscape of the local [[Monaro (New South Wales)|Monaro district]] in the shadow of the [[Snowy Mountains]], which he described as \"unrivalled in the magnificence and grandeur of its beauty\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 28\u201330</ref>\n\n[[File:Paterson Clarence Hughes 1936 (AWM P00835.001).JPG|thumb|left|upright|Hughes, c. December 1936|alt=Studio portrait of young man wearing dark military uniform with pilot's wings and peaked cap]]\nHughes was educated at Cooma Public School until the age of twelve, when the family moved to [[Haberfield, New South Wales|Haberfield]] in [[Sydney]]; his father was by then working as a labourer.<ref name=Alexander30/><ref name=Newton>Newton, ''Australian Air Aces'', pp. 91\u201392</ref> He attended [[Petersham, New South Wales|Petersham Boys' School]], becoming a [[school prefect|prefect]] in 1932 and vice captain the following year.<ref name=Alexander30/> As well as playing sport, he was a keen aircraft modeller and built [[crystal radio]] sets.<ref name=Claason141>Claasen, ''Dogfight'', p. 141</ref> Having attained his [[Intermediate Certificate (Australia)|intermediate certificate]], Hughes entered [[Fort Street High School]] in February 1934.<ref name=Alexander30/> He left after eight months to take up employment at Saunders' Jewellers in [[George Street, Sydney]], and enlisted in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] (RAAF) on 20&nbsp;January 1936.<ref name=Alexander30/><ref name=Garrisson>Garrisson, ''Australian Fighter Aces'', p. 140</ref> Hughes had also applied to, and been accepted by, the [[Royal Australian Navy]], but chose the RAAF.<ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 8</ref>\n\nTraining as an air cadet at [[RAAF Williams#RAAF Williams Point Cook Base|RAAF Point Cook]] near [[Melbourne]], Hughes learnt to fly in [[de Havilland Moth]]s before progressing to [[Westland Wapiti]]s in the middle of the year.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 40, 46</ref> A practical joker who bridled under RAAF discipline, his euphoria during his first solo on 11&nbsp;March 1936 was such that he \"went mad, whistled, sang and almost jumped for joy\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 42, 45</ref> A fellow cadet recalled that Hughes \"loved life and lived it at high pressure\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 36</ref> Upon graduation in December 1936, Hughes was assessed as having \"no outstanding qualities\" despite being \"energetic and keen\".<ref name=Garrisson/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 48</ref> Under a pre-war arrangement between the British and Australian governments, he volunteered for transfer to the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF), and sailed for the United Kingdom in January 1937.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Stephens>Stephens, ''The Royal Australian Air Force'', pp. 84\u201385</ref> His decision to transfer had not been quick or easy; though keen to \"try and do something special\" in England, and intrigued by \"a fascinating picture of easy life, beer and women\" that had been presented to him, in the end he felt that it was simply \"willed\" that he should go.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 47</ref>\n\n==Early RAF service==\nOn 20&nbsp;March 1937, Hughes was granted a five-year short-service commission as a [[pilot officer]] in the RAF.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34376|page=1417|date=20 March 1937}}</ref>  Like some of his compatriots, he refused to exchange his dark-blue RAAF uniform for the lighter-coloured RAF one.<ref name=Claason141/> He undertook advanced flying instruction at [[No. 2 Flying Training School RAF|No.&nbsp;2 Flying Training School]] in [[Digby, Lincolnshire|Digby]], Lincolnshire. Slated to fly bombers, he appealed and in July was posted as a fighter pilot to [[No. 64 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;64 Squadron]], which operated [[Hawker Demon]]s out of [[RAF Martlesham Heath]], Suffolk.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 51\u201352</ref> The squadron was transferred to [[RAF Church Fenton]], Yorkshire, in May 1938.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 54\u201355</ref> Hughes was promoted to [[flying officer]] on 19&nbsp;November.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34577|page=7695|date= 19 November 1938}}</ref> No.&nbsp;64 Squadron subsequently received [[Bristol Blenheim|Bristol Blenheim&nbsp;1F]] twin-engined fighters, and completed its conversion to the type in January 1939.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 64</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n|quote  = There's no use muttering about things... to my mind the chances of living through this are about equal anyhow, and that's all one can ask after all...\n|source = \u2014Hughes to his brother shortly after the outbreak of World War II <ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', pp. 6\u20137</ref>\n|align  = right\n|width  = 31%\n}}\nHughes was promoted to acting [[flight lieutenant]] in November 1939 and became a [[flight commander]] in the newly formed [[No. 234 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;234 Squadron]], which, like No.&nbsp;64 Squadron, came under the control of [[No. 13 Group RAF|No.&nbsp;13 Group]] in the north of England.<ref name=ADB/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. viii, 90, 127</ref> On establishment the previous month at [[RAF Leconfield]], East Yorkshire, No.&nbsp;234 Squadron was equipped with Blenheims, [[Fairey Battle]]s and [[Gloster Gauntlet]]s; it began re-arming with [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s in March 1940 and was operational two months later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/234squadron.cfm|title=234 Squadron|publisher=[[Royal Air Force]]|accessdate=26 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704024902/http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/234squadron.cfm|archivedate=4 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The commanding officer, [[Squadron Leader]] Richard Barnett, rarely flew, and Hughes assumed responsibility for overseeing conversion to the Spitfire.<ref name=Bungay1>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', pp. 1\u20132</ref><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 126, 398</ref> \"More experienced and more mature\" than his fellow pilots, according to historian [[Stephen Bungay]], the Australian \"effectively led\" No.&nbsp;234 Squadron.<ref>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 172</ref> By this time, Hughes had acquired a young [[Airedale Terrier]] known as Flying Officer Butch, who sometimes flew with him\u2014against regulations. He had also met and begun dating Kathleen (\"Kay\") Brodrick of [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]].<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 121\u2013123</ref> On 19&nbsp;June, Hughes and his squadron transferred to [[RAF St&nbsp;Eval]], Cornwall, under the jurisdiction of the newly formed [[No. 10 Group RAF|No.&nbsp;10 Group]] in south-west England.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. viii, xii, 153</ref>\n\n==Battle of Britain==\nAs the [[Battle of Britain]] got under way in July 1940, Hughes shared in No.&nbsp;234 Squadron's first confirmed aerial victories.<ref name=ADB/><ref>Garrisson, ''Australian Fighter Aces'', p. 35</ref> He and his section of two other Spitfires shot down a German [[Junkers Ju&nbsp;88]] attacking convoys near [[Lands End]] on 8&nbsp;July, and another south-east of [[Plymouth]] during a dawn patrol on 28&nbsp;July.<ref name=Newton/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 162, 179</ref> A shared claim for a Ju&nbsp;88 on 27&nbsp;July could not be confirmed as destroyed; after a chase over the water at heights as low as {{convert|50|feet|m}}, the German escaped, despite being struck in the engines and cockpit, and was credited to the section as \"damaged\".<ref name=Few178>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 178\u2013179</ref><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', pp. 64\u201365</ref> German records, made available post-war, confirm that a Junkers 88A piloted by Leutnant Ruckdeschel, was lost on this day.<ref>Mason, ''Battle Over Britain'', p.153</ref> On 1&nbsp;August, Hughes was seconded from No.&nbsp;234 Squadron to help set up the only [[Gloster Gladiator]]-equipped unit to operate during the Battle of Britain, [[No. 247 Squadron RAF|No.&nbsp;247 (China British) Squadron]] in Plymouth.<ref name=ADB/><ref>Shores; Williams, ''Aces High'', p. 48</ref> The same day, he married Kay Brodrick, who likened him to [[Errol Flynn]], in the [[register office]] at [[Bodmin]], Cornwall.<ref name=ADB/><ref name=Bungay310>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 310</ref> Apart from Flying Officer Butch, the witnesses were strangers; Kay arrived alone, and no-one from No.&nbsp;234 Squadron could attend.<ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 72</ref><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 180</ref> Barnett was transferred out of No.&nbsp;234 Squadron on 13&nbsp;August, and Hughes took temporary command until the arrival of Squadron Leader Joe \"Spike\" O'Brien four days later.<ref name=Bungay1/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 198, 210</ref> By now the fighting was intensifying over southern England, and the squadron relocated from St&nbsp;Eval to [[RAF Middle Wallop]], Hampshire, on 14&nbsp;August.<ref name=Bungay1/><ref name=Price66>Price, ''Spitfire Mk.I/II Aces'', p. 66</ref> Almost immediately after Hughes landed the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' bombed the airfield; several ground staff and civilian workers were killed, but No.&nbsp;234 Squadron's Spitfires escaped damage.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 199</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n|quote  = No-one had more air sense than Pat&nbsp;... his only problem was that he got too close but that was his way.\n|source = \u2014Joe Roddis, Hughes' [[Fitter (occupation)|fitter]] <ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 263, 344</ref>\n|align  = right\n|width  = 31%\n}}\nIt was following No.&nbsp;234 Squadron's move to Middle Wallop that Hughes began to score heavily against German fighters.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Price66/> On 15&nbsp;August, in one of the costliest engagements of the Battle of Britain, known thereafter to the ''Luftwaffe'' as \"Black Thursday\", Hughes claimed victories (one of them shared) over two [[Messerschmitt Bf 110]]s.<ref name=Newton/><ref>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 218</ref>  He again achieved dual success on 16, 18 and 26&nbsp;August, all six victims being [[Messerschmitt Bf&nbsp;109]]s brought down in the vicinity of the [[Isle of Wight]].<ref name=Newton/> Whereas in July he had fired at his targets from a range of {{convert|150|to|50|yd}}, it was now his habit to close to {{convert|30|yd}}, approximately three Spitfire lengths, before delivering his final burst; he also made head-on attacks against enemy aircraft.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 215</ref>  He had a narrow escape on the 16th after his second victory of the day, when he chased a quartet of [[Junkers Ju&nbsp;87]]s and had his [[tailplane]] shot up from behind by another Bf&nbsp;109; he dived and forced the German to overshoot, then broke off having exhausted his ammunition firing at his former attacker. In the pub with Kay and his squadron mates that evening, Hughes jokingly told his wife, \"In case of accidents make sure you marry again\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 207\u2013210</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1969-094-18, Dornier Do 17 und Supermarine Spitfire.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.28|Dornier Do 17 and Supermarine Spitfire, 1940|alt=Twin-engined, twin-finned aircraft in flight with single-engined aircraft in lower background]]\nOn 3&nbsp;September, Hughes' promotion to [[substantive rank|substantive]] flight lieutenant was promulgated in ''[[The London Gazette]]''.<ref name=ADB/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34954|page=5715|date= 3 September 1940}}</ref> He claimed three Me&nbsp;110s in the space of fifteen minutes south of [[Haslemere]] on 4&nbsp;September, two Bf&nbsp;109s while patrolling [[Kenley]] the following day, and a Bf&nbsp;109 destroyed plus one probable near [[Dover]] on 6&nbsp;September; he had to break off combat with the last-mentioned when its tanks ruptured, covering Hughes' canopy in oil.<ref name=Newton/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 247\u2013250</ref> One of his victims on 5&nbsp;September may have been Oberleutnant [[Franz von Werra]], who was captured and subsequently became famous as \"[[the One That Got Away (1957 film)|the one that got away]]\".<ref name=ADB/><ref>Claasen, ''Dogfight'', pp. 142\u2013143</ref> Hughes and his prot\u00e9g\u00e9, [[Bob Doe]], claimed half of No.&nbsp;234 Squadron's victories between mid-August and early September.<ref>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', pp. 172, 196</ref>\n\nHughes was killed in action on the evening of 7&nbsp;September 1940, after he intercepted a [[Dornier Do&nbsp;17]] bomber taking part in a large-scale attack on London.<ref name=ADB/><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', pp. 166\u2013167</ref> His Spitfire crashed in a field between [[Sundridge, Kent|Sundridge]] and [[Bessels Green]] in [[Kent]]. He apparently bailed out, but his parachute failed to open; his body was found in a garden on Main Road, Sundridge, not far from the wreck of his Spitfire. The Dornier came down in the [[River Darent]].<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 260\u2013261, 343</ref> No.&nbsp;234 Squadron lost its commanding officer, O'Brien, in the same action.<ref name=Bungay310/><ref name=Bishop>Bishop, ''Battle of Britain'', p. 305</ref> Mystery surrounds exactly how Hughes came to grief, though his close-in tactics are believed to have played a major part in it.<ref name=Newton/> The strain of regular combat without respite, manifesting itself in fatigue and spots before the eyes, may also have contributed.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 250\u2013254, 259\u2013260</ref><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 161</ref> He is generally thought to have collided with flying wreckage from the crippled German bomber, rendering his Spitfire uncontrollable.<ref name=Garrisson/><ref name=Bishop/><ref>Wilson, ''The Brotherhood of Airmen'', p. 67</ref> It is also possible that Hughes accidentally rammed his target. Further speculation suggested that he was the victim of [[friendly fire]] from another British fighter attacking the same Dornier, or was struck by German bullets from a Bf&nbsp;109.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Bungay472>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 472</ref> Some observers on the ground, including [[Coal mining|collier]] Charles Hall, maintained that Hughes rammed the Dornier on purpose.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 261</ref> Four days after his death, No.&nbsp;234 Squadron was moved back to the relative quiet of Cornwall.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Alexander265>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 265</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{Quote box\n|quote  = Everyone talks about the wrong people&nbsp;... the self-publicists. Now who has ever heard of Pat Hughes? He saved our squadron, and he shot down a lot more than others I could name. But he died you see. That was a blow.\n|source = \u2014Bob Doe, quoted in 2000 <ref>Bungay, ''The Most Dangerous Enemy'', p. 400</ref>\n|align  = right\n|width  = 31%\n}}\nThe top-scoring Australian [[flying ace]] of the Battle of Britain and one of fourteen Australian fighter pilots killed during the battle,<ref name=Garrisson/><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 1</ref> Hughes has been described as \"the inspiration and driving force behind No.&nbsp;234 Squadron RAF\".<ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 167</ref> He is generally credited with seventeen confirmed victories\u2014fourteen solo and three shared.<ref name=Newton/><ref name=Price66/> This tally puts him among the top ten [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] Battle of Britain aces.<ref name=Alexander263>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 263</ref><ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', p. 283</ref> It also ranks him among the three highest-scoring Australians of World War&nbsp;II, after [[Clive Caldwell]] with thirty victories (twenty-seven solo and three shared) and [[Adrian Goldsmith]] with seventeen (sixteen solo and one shared).<ref name=Alexander263/><ref>Newton, ''Australian Air Aces'', pp. 117\u2013118</ref>\n\nA war widow after barely five weeks of marriage, Kay Hughes was inconsolable in her loss: \"I wept until I could cry no more\".<ref name=Alexander265/> Flying Officer Butch ran out of the [[mess]] on the day of his master's death, and was never seen again.<ref name=Alexander264>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 264\u2013265</ref> Following a service at St James', [[Sutton-on-Hull]], on 13&nbsp;September 1940, Hughes was buried in the churchyard at Row&nbsp;G, Grave&nbsp;4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2414101/HUGHES,%20PATERSON%20CLARENCE|title=Hughes, Paterson Clarence|publisher=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> A week later, Kay discovered she was pregnant, but eventually miscarried.<ref name=Alexander265/> She subsequently drove ambulances for the British war effort.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 335</ref> News of his son's marriage came as \"a complete surprise\" to Percy Hughes, who only learned of his daughter-in-law's existence from the Australian Air Board's casualty letter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://recordsearch.naa.gov.au/SearchNRetrieve/Interface/ViewImage.aspx?B=1054979&S=1|title= Hughes, Paterson Clarence&nbsp;\u2013 Casualty File|publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]]|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> Having married three more times after Hughes' death, Kay died on 28&nbsp;June 1983 and, in accordance with her wishes, her ashes were buried with her first husband, whose headstone was amended to read \"In loving memory of his wife Kathleen\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 335\u2013336</ref>\n\nHughes was posthumously awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (DFC) on 22&nbsp;October 1940 for his \"skill and determination\" as a flight commander and \"gallantry in his attacks on the enemy\"; Squadron Leader O'Brien had recommended the decoration a week before their deaths.<ref name=DFC/><ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 264</ref> Kay was presented with the medal at [[Buckingham Palace]] on 23&nbsp;June 1942.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47337212 |title=Late Sydney pilot |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=24 June 1942 |accessdate=16 June 2015 |page=2}}</ref> In Australia, Hughes is commemorated at Christ's Church, [[Kiama]], with a memorial tablet placed by his sister Muriel.<ref name=ADB/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warmemorialsregister.nsw.gov.au/content/paterson-clarence-hughes-memorial-tablet|title=Paterson Clarence Hughes Memorial Tablet|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales Government]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref>  A special memorial is dedicated to him at Monaghan Hayes Place, Cooma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cooma.nsw.gov.au/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=914:monaghan-hayes-place&catid=202&Itemid=103|title=Flight Lieutenant Paterson Clarence Hughes DFC Memorial|publisher=[[Cooma-Monaro Shire|Cooma\u2013Monaro Shire Council]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> His name appears on the [[Battle of Britain Roll of Honour]] in [[Westminster Abbey]], and on supplementary panel&nbsp;12 in the Commemorative Area of the [[Australian War Memorial]] (AWM), [[Canberra]].<ref>Newton, ''A Few of {{'}}the Few{{'}}'', pp. 267\u2013268</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.awm.gov.au/research/people/roll_of_honour/person/R1719963/|title=Roll of Honour&nbsp;\u2013 Paterson Clarence Hughes|publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> The AWM also holds his DFC and service medals in its collection.<ref name=AWM>{{cite  web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/collection/REL/17986.001 |title= Distinguished Flying Cross: Flight Lieutenant P.C. Hughes, 234 Squadron RAF|publisher=Australian War Memorial|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> Kay had given the medals to her sisters-in-law to pass on to Percy in the 1950s and, after being lost during an [[Anzac Day]] parade in the 1960s, they went through several family members' hands before turning up in the safe of the Kiama [[Country Women's Association]]; they were donated to the AWM in 1990.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 341\u2013343</ref> On 7&nbsp;September 2005, Charles Hall's sons dedicated a plaque in Hughes' honour at the house where he fell in Main Road, Sundridge; Bob Doe attended, expressing his thanks for \"an Australian who came to help us when we needed him\".<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 343</ref> [[Shoreham Aircraft Museum]] in Kent unveiled a memorial stone to Hughes at Sundridge on 23&nbsp;August 2008.<ref>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', p. 344</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shoreham-aircraft-museum.co.uk/memorials-hughes.htm|title= Local Memorials Project: Flight Lieutenant Pat Hughes|publisher=[[Shoreham Aircraft Museum]]|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> On 15&nbsp;September 2014, the AWM's daily [[Last Post|Last Post Ceremony]] was dedicated to Hughes' memory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/PAFU2014/343.01/|title=The Last Post Ceremony commemorating the service of Flight Lieutenant Paterson Clarence Hughes DFC, No. 234 Squadron, RAF, Second World War|publisher=Australian War Memorial|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Combat record==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=\"40\" align=center|No.\n!width=\"140\" align=center|Date\n!width=\"70\" align=center|Flying\n!width=\"180\" align=center|Foe\n!width=\"180\" align=center|Result\n!width=\"180\" align=center|Location\n|-\n|1\n|8 July 1940\n|[[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]]\n|[[Junkers Ju 88]]\n|Destroyed (shared) <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186>Shores; Williams, ''Aces High'', p. 186</ref>\n|SE [[Lands End]]\n|-\n|\u2013\n|27 July 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Junkers Ju 88\n|Damaged (shared) <ref name=Few178/><ref>Unconfirmed destroyed according to Newton, ''Australian Air Aces'', p. 92</ref>\n|SE Lands End\n|-\n|2\n|28 July 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Junkers Ju 88\n|Destroyed (shared) <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|SE [[Plymouth]]\n|-\n|3\n|15 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|[[Messerschmitt Bf 110]]\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Few204>Alexander, ''Australia's Few'', pp. 204\u2013206</ref>\n|[[Middle Wallop]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Isle of Wight]]\n|-\n|4\n|15 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt  Bf 110\n|Destroyed (shared) <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Few204/>\n|SW [[Swanage]]\n|-\n|5\n|16 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|[[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|6\n|16 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|7\n|18 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|8\n|18 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|9\n|26 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|10\n|26 August 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Isle of Wight\n|-\n|11\n|4 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 110\n|Destroyed <ref name=Shores186/><ref name=Newton91>Newton, ''Australian Air Aces'', p. 91</ref>\n|[[Haslemere]]\u2013[[Brighton]]\n|-\n|12\n|4 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 110\n|Destroyed <ref name=Shores186/><ref name=Newton91/>\n|Haslemere\u2013Brighton\n|-\n|13\n|4 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 110\n|Destroyed <ref name=Shores186/><ref name=Newton91/>\n|Haslemere\u2013Brighton\n|-\n|14\n|5 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|[[Eastchurch]]\n|-\n|15\n|5 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|S [[Manston, Kent|Manston]]\n|-\n|16\n|6 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|[[Dover]]\n|-\n|\u2013\n|6 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|Messerschmitt Bf 109E\n|Probable <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|Dover\n|-\n|17\n|7 September 1940\n|Spitfire\n|[[Dornier Do 17]]\n|Destroyed <ref name=Newton/><ref name=Shores186/>\n|London\u2013Brighton\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Alexander|first=Kristen|title=Australia's Few and the Battle of Britain|publisher=NewSouth Publishing|location=Sydney|year=2014|isbn=978-1-74224-694-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bishop|first=Patrick|title=Battle of Britain: A Day-by-Day Chronicle|publisher=[[Quercus (publisher)|Quercus Publishing]]|location=London|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84724-984-5|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/battleofbritaind0000bish}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bungay| first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Bungay|year=2000| title=The Most Dangerous Enemy: A History of the Battle of Britain | location=London| publisher= Aurom Press |isbn=978-1-85410-801-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Claasen| first=Adam|year=2004| title=Dogfight: The Battle of Britain | location=Auckland| publisher= Exisle Publishing |isbn=978-1-921497-28-5}}\n* {{cite book|last=Garrisson|first=A.D.|title=Australian Fighter Aces 1914\u20131953 |url=http://airpower.airforce.gov.au/Publications/Details/220/Australian-Fighter-Aces-1914\u20131953.aspx|publisher=Air Power Studies Centre|location=Fairbairn, Australian Capital Territory|year=1999|isbn=978-0-642-26540-1}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mason |first=Francis K. |title=Battle Over Britain |publisher=Aston |location=Bourne End |year=1990 |isbn=0-946627-15-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Newton |first=Dennis|year=1990 |title=A Few of 'the Few': Australians and the Battle of Britain|location=Canberra |publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]] |isbn=978-0-642-14991-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Newton| first=Dennis|year=1996| title=Australian Air Aces| location=Fyshwyck, Australian Capital Territory| publisher=Aerospace Publications|isbn=978-1-875671-25-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Price|first=Alfred|title=Spitfire Mk.I/II Aces 1939\u201341|year=1996|publisher=[[Osprey Publishing|Osprey]] |location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-85532-627-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shores| first=Christopher| last2=Williams|first2= Clive|year=1966| title=Aces High: The Fighter Aces of the British and Commonwealth Air Forces in World War II |location=London|publisher= Neville Spearman |isbn=|oclc=8013035}}\n* {{cite book|last=Stephens| first=Alan|origyear=2001|year=2006| title=The Royal Australian Air Force: A History|location=London| publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-555541-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wilson| first=David|year=2005| title=The Brotherhood of Airmen| location=Crows Nest, New South Wales| publisher=[[Allen & Unwin]] |isbn=1-74114-333-0}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://recordsearch.naa.gov.au/SearchNRetrieve/Interface/ViewImage.aspx?B=5250414&S=1 National Archives of Australia: Personal File]\n*[http://www.suttonandwawnemuseum.org.uk/pch.htm Sutton & Wawne Museum: A brief biography of the Australian fighter pilot killed during the Battle of Britain, and buried in Sutton churchyard in 1940]\n*[http://www.battleofbritain1940.net/0037.html Battle of Britain Historical Society: Saturday, September 7th 1940]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hughes, Pat}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Australian World War II flying aces]]\n[[Category:People from Cooma, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Royal Australian Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:The Few]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force pilots of World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Ian Rose", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBattle of Britain:Comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paterson_Clarence_Hughes"}
{"title_page": "Adrian Dunbar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Adrian Dunbar\n| image           = Adrian Dunbar - Actor (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Dunbar in 2014\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1958|8|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Enniskillen]], [[County Fermanagh]], [[Ireland]]\n| occupation      = Actor, \nScreenwriter, Director\n| notabale work   = [[Ashes to Ashes]] (2009)\n[[Line of Duty]] (2012-present)\n| yearsactive     = 1984\u2013present\n| spouse          = Anna Nygh (1986&ndash;present)\n}}\n\n'''Adrian Dunbar''' (born 1 August 1958) is an [[Irish people|Irish]] actor and director from [[Enniskillen]], [[County Fermanagh]], [[Ireland]], best known for his television and theatre work. Dunbar co-wrote and starred in the 1991 film, ''[[Hear My Song]]'', nominated for Best Original Screenplay at the [[BAFTA]] awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9E0CE2D71E39F93AA25752C0A964958260|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Hear My Song (1991) Review/Film; Irish Tenor Is Focus Of Intrigue and Blarney|author=Janet Maslin|date=19 January 1992}}</ref>\n\nHe has played Superintendent Ted Hastings in the [[BBC One]] thriller ''[[Line of Duty]]'' since 2012. He has also appeared as Alan Cox in ''[[The Jump (1998 TV series)|The Jump]]'', Martin Summers in ''[[Ashes to Ashes (TV series)|Ashes to Ashes]]'', Richard Plantagenet in ''[[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown]]'', and as Father Flaherty in ''[[Broken (TV series)|Broken]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nDunbar was born and brought up in [[Enniskillen]], [[County Fermanagh]], in [[Ireland]], the eldest of seven siblings. He was educated by the [[Irish Christian Brothers]] before attending the [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]] in [[London]].<ref>https://michaeldsellers.wordpress.com/2007/07/09/eod-star-biographies-adrian-dunbar</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDunbar has appeared in such notable films as ''[[My Left Foot (film)|My Left Foot]]'', ''[[The Crying Game]]'', and ''[[The General (1998 film)|The General]]''. He has also had leading roles in the films ''Triggermen'', ''Shooters'', ''How Harry Became A Tree'' (with [[Colm Meaney]]), ''[[Richard III (1995 film)|Richard III]]'', and ''[[Widows' Peak]]''.\n\nOn television, he starred in the first episode of ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'', giving a performance as an innocent murder suspect with amnesia, and also the last episode of ''[[A Touch of Frost]]'', and has been in many British productions, including ''Tough Love'', ''[[Inspector Morse (TV series)|Inspector Morse]]'', ''Kidnapped'', ''Murphy's Law'', ''Murder in Mind'', ''Ashes to Ashes'' and the 2005 re-staging of ''[[The Quatermass Experiment (film)|The Quatermass Experiment]]''.\n\nDunbar's theatre credits include: ''The Shaughraun'' and ''[[Exiles (play)|Exiles]]'' at Dublin's [[Abbey Theatre]]; ''Real Dreams'' and ''The Danton Affair'' at the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]; ''[[King Lear]]'', ''Pope's Wedding'', ''Saved and Up To The Sun And Down To The Centre'' at [[Royal Court Theatre]], ''[[Conversations on a homecoming]]'' at the [[Lyric Theatre (Belfast)]]; ''A Trinity of Two'' (as [[Oscar Wilde]]) at Dublin's Liberty Hall Theatre; ''Boeing Boeing'' (London, 2007). He directed a critically acclaimed production of ''[[Philadelphia Here I Come!]]''.\n\nIn 2008 he starred in and co-directed ''Brendan at the Chelsea'' by [[Janet Behan]], playing [[Brendan Behan]]. The play was the first to be staged in the Naughton Studio in the new [[Lyric Theatre (Belfast)]] after it reopened in 2011 and is being revived for a tour to Theatre Row in [[New York City|New York]] in September 2013.\n\nHe played the role of Aufidius in the [[BBC radio|BBC Radio]] production of ''[[Coriolanus (play)|Coriolanus]]''. He also made a guest appearance in the BBC Radio 4 series [[Baldi (radio)|Baldi]], and appeared on stage as [[Vermeer]] in an adaptation of ''[[Girl with a Pearl Earring (play)|Girl with a Pearl Earring]]''.\n\nIn 2008, Dunbar played the role of Philip Conolly in the critically acclaimed ''[[The Last Confession of Alexander Pearce]]''. Dunbar starred alongside fellow [[Northern Irish]] actor [[Ciar\u00e1n McMenamin]] in the remote rain-forests of north west [[Tasmania]]. He has also joined the cast of the British [[police procedural]] [[television series]], [[Line of Duty]] in 2012, portraying the role of Superintendent Ted Hastings continuing on in this role for Series 2 (2014), Series 3 (2016), Series 4 (2017) and Series 5 (2019).\n\nDunbar is also a theatre director who staged productions for the Happy Days Enniskillen International Beckett Festival.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Masters|first1=Time|title=Beckett festival to feature play in the dark|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-32319040|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Slater|first1=Sasha|title=Going to the Opera|url=http://sophiehunter.net/post/123316988800/going-to-the-opera-by-sasha-slater-harpers-bazaar|website=Harper's Bazaar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Thorpe|first1=Vanessa|title=Sophie Hunter: The opera director who has to dodge paparazzie|url=http://sophiehunter.net/post/123849640525/sophie-hunter-the-opera-director-who-has-to-dodge|website=Sophie Hunter Central}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kennedy|first1=Maev|title=Happy Days festival's Beckett treats to include a German Godot|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/apr/15/happy-days-festival-samuel-beckett-enniskillen-northern-ireland|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nHe played the mysterious character Martin Summers in the second series of ''[[Ashes to Ashes (TV series)|Ashes to Ashes]]''. In 2014 he played the title character in a BBC comedy drama ''Walter''.<ref>http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04d8y38</ref>\n\nDunbar also starred as Jim Hogan on the [[Virgin Media Television (Ireland)|Virgin Media Television]] original drama, ''Blood''.\n\n==Other media==\n{{BLP sources section|date=June 2017}}\n*He was cast as [[Bail Organa]] for ''[[Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace]]'' and appeared in costume in publicity stills, but his scene was cut, and the character was re-cast with [[Jimmy Smits]] for later films. Dunbar's likeness was [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] into the appearance of the character [[List of Star Wars characters#A|Bail Antilles]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4u83irHK2JA</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/aug/14/news2</ref>\n*He fronts his own band,<ref>[http://www.daracu.ie Adie Dunbar and the Jonahs]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928070012/http://www.daracu.ie/ |date=28 September 2007 }}</ref> which has played in such American venues as [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and [[Austin, Texas]].\n*He sings \"The Curragh of Kildare\" with [[Brian Kennedy (singer)|Brian Kennedy]] on Kennedy's ''On Song'', and fronts this song with his own band.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/tracks/nzmj98</ref>\n*He narrates the popular TV series ''[[The Estate (TV series)|The Estate]]'' as well as the [[audiobook]] productions of [[Eoin Colfer]]'s ''[[Artemis Fowl (series)|Artemis Fowl]]'' series, a bestselling novel.\n*He played a minor role in ''[[The Dawning]]'' (1988), alongside [[Anthony Hopkins]] and [[Hugh Grant]], which led to further early roles in his acting career.\n\n==Awards==\n\n===BAFTA Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\"| [[BAFTA Awards]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:25em;\"| Nominated work\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30em;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:5em;\"| Result\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Line of Duty]]''\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Hear My Song]]''\n| Best Screenplay\n| {{nominated}}\n|}\n\n===Irish Film & Television Academy Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\"| [[IFTA Awards]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:25em;\"| Nominated work\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30em;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:5em;\"| Result\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Line of Duty]]''\n| Actor in a Lead Role in Drama\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nDunbar has a daughter and stepson from his 1986 marriage to the Australian actress Anna Nygh. He lives in [[Crouch End]], North London. Dunbar received an [[honorary degree]] of [[Doctor of Letters]] from the [[University of Ulster]] in June 2009 in recognition of his services to acting.<ref>[http://news.ulster.ac.uk/releases/2009/4485.html Honorary Degree for Leading Ulster Actor Dunbar] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200244/http://news.ulster.ac.uk/releases/2009/4485.html |date=3 March 2016 }}, University of Ulster website, 30 June 2009.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Sky Bandits (1986 film)|Sky Bandits]]'' || Mechanic ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1988 || ''[[A World Apart (film)|A World Apart]]'' || Le Roux ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Dawning]]'' || Capt. Rankin ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|1989 || ''Unusual Ground Floor Conversion'' || Alan Simpson || Short film\n|-\n| ''[[My Left Foot (film)|My Left Foot]]'' || Peter ||\n|-\n| ''[[Dealers (film)|Dealers]]'' || Lennon Mayhew ||\n|-\n| 1991 || ''[[Hear My Song]]'' || Micky O'Neill ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1992 || ''The Playboys'' || Mick ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Crying Game]]'' || Maguire ||\n|-\n| 1994 ||''[[Widows' Peak]]'' || Godfrey Doyle-Counihan ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|1995 || ''[[Innocent Lies]]'' || Alan Cross ||\n|-\n| ''The Near Room'' || Charlie Colquhoun || \n|-\n| ''[[Richard III (1995 film)|Richard III]]'' || James Tyrell || \n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[The General (1998 film)|The General]]'' || Noel Curley ||\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace]]'' || [[Bail Organa|Senator Bail Organa]] || Deleted scene\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2000 || ''Last Orders'