\"3\"|2005 || ''[[Kidnapped (2005 miniseries)|Kidnapped]]'' || Alexander Balfour / Ebenezer Balfour ||rowspan=3| TV Movie\n|-\n| ''[[The Quatermass Experiment (film)|The Quatermass Experiment]]'' || Detective Lomax\n|-\n| ''[[Child of Mine (2005 film)|Child of Mine]]'' || Alfie Palmer\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[The Whistleblowers]]'' || Chris Clayton || Episode: \"Starters\"\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Whistleblower (Irish TV series)|Whistleblower]]'' || Florence Wycherley || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Ashes to Ashes (TV series)|Ashes to Ashes]]'' || Martin Summers || 8 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2010 || ''[[A Touch of Frost]]'' || Gerry Berland || Episodes: \"If Dogs Run Free\", Parts 1 & 2\n|-\n| ''[[Mo (2010 film)|Mo]]'' || David Trimble || TV Movie\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2011 || ''[[Silk (TV series)|Silk]]'' || Joe Gillespie QC || Episode: \"Three Sheets to the Wind\"\n|-\n| ''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death in Paradise]]'' || Aidan Miles || Episodes: \"Music of Murder\" and \"Amongst Us\"\n|-\n| 2011\u20142013|| ''[[World's Most Dangerous Roads]]'' || Narrator || 09 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2012 || ''[[Scott & Bailey]]'' || Det. Supt. Rick Wallis || Episode: \"Pipe Dreams\"\n|-\n| ''[[Silent Witness]]'' || Sean Delaney || Episodes: \"Fear\", Parts 1 & 2\n|-\n| ''The Life and Adventures of Nick Nickleby'' || Ralph Nickleby || 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\u2014present || ''[[Line of Duty]]'' || Supt. Ted Hastings || 29 episodes\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Jo (TV series)|Jo]]'' || Olivier Cattan || Episode: \"Place Vend\u00f4me\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2014 || ''[[Walter (2014 film)|Walter]]'' || DI Walter Gambon || TV Movie\n|-\n| ''[[A Touch of Cloth]]'' || Damien Vull || Episodes: \"Too Cloth for Comfort\", Parts 1 & 2\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown]]'' || Plantagenet || Episodes: \"Henry VI\", Parts 1 & 2\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Broken (TV series)|Broken]]'' || Father Peter Flaherty ||rowspan=2| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2018 || ''Blood'' || Jim Hogan\n|-\n| 2019 || ''Red Nose Bodyguard'' || Policeman / Supt. Ted Hastings || ''[[Red Nose Day 2019]]'' special\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0001160|name=Adrian Dunbar}}\n* [http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/line-of-dutys-adrian-dunbar-attacked-for-describing-ruc-as-sectarian-by-murdered-officers-daughter-35670885.html Adrian Dunbar attacked for describing RUC as sectarian by murdered officer's daughter], belfasttelegraph.co.uk; accessed 4 June 2017.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunbar, Adrian}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Enniskillen]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Guildhall School of Music and Drama]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish male actors]]\n[[Category:Male stage actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Male television actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Male film actors from Northern Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "51.37.1.41", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrian_Dunbar"}
{"title_page": "Grant Hanley", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Grant Hanley\n| image = Grant Hanley 2018.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Hanley playing for [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in 2018\n| fullname = Grant Campbell Hanley<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|23322|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|267 BC|11|20|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman/>\n| birth_place = [[Dumfries]], Scotland\n| height = {{convert|1.87|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rovers.co.uk/team/player-profile/index.aspx?playerid=417715&tcmuri=96232 |title=Player Profile \u2013 Grant Hanley |accessdate=15 March 2011 |publisher=Blackburn Rovers F.C.}}</ref>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n| clubnumber = 5\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n| youthyears2 = 2004\u20132006\n| youthclubs2 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n| youthyears3 = 2006\u20132008\n| youthclubs3 = [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]\n| youthyears4 = 2008\u20132010\n| youthclubs4 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n| years1 = 2010\u20132016\n| clubs1 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n| caps1 = 183\n| goals1 = 8\n| years2 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs2 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n| caps2 = 10\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs3 = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n| caps3 = 51\n| goals3 = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 2010\u20132011\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2010\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2011\u2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 29\n| nationalgoals3 = 1\n| club-update = 21:35, 22 January 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 30 June 2018 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Grant Campbell Hanley''' (born 20 November 1991) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defender (association football)|defender]] for {{English football updater|NorwichC}} club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]. He has previously played for [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].\n\n==Early years==\nHanley was born in [[Dumfries]], [[Dumfries and Galloway]].<ref name=Hugman/> He was involved at youth level with local club [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]], [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] and with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] before he joined [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] as a 16-year-old in 2008.<ref>[http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news/article/muirheads-career-built-on-solid-bricks/ Muirhead's career built on solid bricks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616125249/http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news/article/muirheads-career-built-on-solid-bricks/ |date=16 June 2012 }} Scottish Football League, 14 January 2011</ref><ref name=NewCH>[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/scotland/2010/05/24/i-can-be-the-new-colin-hendry-for-scotland-blackburn-vows-scots-under-19-skipper-grant-hanley-86908-22281189/ I can be the new Colin Hendry for Scotland & Blackburn, vows Scots under 19 skipper Grant Hanley] ''Daily Record'', 24 May 2010</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Blackburn Rovers===\nAt Rovers, Hanley was captain of the under-18 team.<ref name=NewCH/> Hanley made his [[Premier League]] debut for Rovers in a 1\u20130 win at Aston Villa on 9 May 2010.<ref name=BRProf>{{cite web |title=Grant Hanley first team profile |url=http://www.rovers.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10303~51151,00.html |publisher=Blackburn Rovers F.C. |accessdate=10 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505200558/http://www.rovers.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10303~51151%2C00.html |archivedate=5 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com//football/match_facts/0,,11065_3151896,00+en-USS_01DBC.html |title=Aston Villa 0 \u2013 1 Blackburn |website=Sky Sports |date=9 May 2010 |accessdate=9 May 2010}}</ref> Hanley committed his future when he signed a new five-year deal with Blackburn on 21 July 2010.<ref>[http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/sport/8284970.Blackburn_Rovers_defender_Hanley_pens_five_year_contract/ Blackburn Rovers defender Hanley pens five-year contract] ''Lancashire Telegraph'', 22 July 2010</ref>\n\nHanley made his first Premier League appearance of season 2010\u201311 as a 67th-minute substitute in a 1\u20131 draw at home to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} He made his [[FA Cup]] debut on 8 January 2011, against [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in a 1\u20130 victory at Ewood Park.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/match/2011/jan/08/blackburn-v-qpr Blackburn Rovers v QPR Match facts] ''The Guardian'', 8 January 2011</ref> On 5 March 2011, Hanley scored his first goal for Rovers in a 3\u20132 defeat against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] at [[Craven Cottage]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9411020.stm Fulham 3\u20132 Blackburn] ''BBC Sport'', 5 March 2011</ref> That was the last of his nine Blackburn first team appearances that season although he was to make his international debut at the end of the season.<ref name=qosintl/> On 31 December 2011, Hanley started and scored the winning goal in a 3\u20132 win against local rivals [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16373420.stm Match winner Grant Hanley hails Blackburn Rovers youth] ''BBC Sport'', 31 December 2011</ref><ref>[http://football.uk.reuters.com/leagues/premiership/news/2011/12/31/489C36A6-33D7-11E1-AC36-1AE57F33923B.php Blackburn stun United, Spurs and Chelsea slip up] Reuters, 31 December 2011</ref> This win lifted Blackburn off the bottom of the table.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/16324998.stm Man Utd 2\u20133 Blackburn] ''BBC Sport'', 31 December 2011</ref> On 14 April 2012, in a Premier League fixture against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] at the [[Liberty Stadium]], he suffered ankle ligament damage.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Hanley made 28 appearances and scored one goal in all competitions for Rovers but the club was relegated into the [[Football League Championship|Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/matchday/league-table.html |title=Premier League Table |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2012\u201313 season Hanley maintained his first team place and formed a [[2012\u201313 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season#Appearances and goals|partnership]] with [[Scott Dann]]. At the end of the season, he signed a five-year contract with the club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Transfer news: Blackburn give Grant Hanley long-term contract at Ewood Park |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12691/8754287/Transfer-news-Blackburn-give-Grant-Hanley-long-term-contract-at-Ewood-Park |website=Sky Sports |date=4 June 2013 |accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter Dann left for [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in January 2014, Hanley was appointed as the new [[Captain (association football)|captain]] of the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delighted for the captain |url=http://www.rovers.co.uk/news/article/delighted-for-the-captain-1336772.aspx |publisher=Blackburn Rovers F.C. |date=3 February 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\nOn 21 July 2016, Hanley signed for newly relegated Championship club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on a five-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news |title=Grant Hanley: Newcastle United sign Blackburn Rovers captain |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36857862 |website=BBC Sport |date=21 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> He was handed the number 5 shirt, previously worn by [[Georginio Wijnaldum]].\nHe scored his first goal for the club in the 79th minute in a 6\u20130 win versus [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at [[Loftus Road]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37282510 |title=Queens Park Rangers 0-6 Newcastle United |date=14 September 2016 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Norwich City===\n====2017&ndash;18====\nOn 30 August 2017, Hanley joined [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] on a four-year deal for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{citenews|title=Grant Hanley joins Norwich City|url=https://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2017/august/grant-hanley-joins-norwich-city/|publisher=Norwich City F.C.|date=30 August 2017}}</ref> He made his debut on 9 September 2017, coming on as a substitute in a 1\u20130 win over [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] at [[Carrow Road]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41132799 |title=Norwich City 1-0 Birmingham City |date=9 September 2017 |website=BBC Sport|access-date=9 September 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref> Although he had been something of an emergency buy, with Norwich having started the season with a number of injuries and playing inexperienced centre backs, Hanley soon became a regular in the team, often being deployed as one of three centre halves with [[Timm Klose]] and [[Christoph Zimmermann]]. He ultimately made 32 league appearances for Norwich during the 2017\u201318 season, plus two in the FA Cup. One of his most memorable contributions came in the derby game against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on 18 February. Ipswich had gone 1\u20130 up in the 89th minute and seemed set for a first win over Norwich in nine years. However, deep into added time, Hanley chased a ball to the byline and crossed it back into the goal area, allowing Klose to head it home for an equaliser.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43020998 |title=Norwich City 1-1 Ipswich Town |date=18 February 2018 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 January 2019 }}</ref> The following month, on 17 March, Hanley scored his first goal for Norwich, the second in a 3\u20132 win over [[Reading F.C.|Reading]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43353592 |title=Norwich City 3-2 Reading |date=17 March 2018 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n====2018&ndash;19====\nAt the beginning of the 2018&ndash;19 season, with [[Russell Martin (footballer)|Russell Martin]] leaving the club, Hanley was appointed Norwich's new club captain<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2018/august/grant-hanley-birmingham/ |title=Grant Hanley: Being named captain is a huge honour |date=1 August 2018 |publisher=Norwich City F.C. |accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> ahead of [[Ivo Pinto]], who had deputised for Martin for much of the previous season. He played in Norwich's opening six league games, getting his second goal for the club in a 4\u20133 defeat against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]];<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45066581 |title=Norwich City 3-4 West Bromwich Albion: Jay Rodriguez efforts please Baggies boss |date=11 August 2018 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> however, he was then injured in training.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45522509 |title=Grant Hanley: Norwich defender out for six weeks with quad injury |date=14 September 2018 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> During his absence, Klose and Zimmermann established themselves at centre-back, with [[Ben Godfrey]] also becoming a regular choice, and Hanley was restricted to a few appearances as substitute on his return. When he finally started a game, an [[FA Cup]] tie against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], he was sent off in the first fifteen minutes for a professional foul on [[Ronan Curtis]] and Norwich went on to lose 1\u20130.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46707005 |title=Norwich City 0-1 Portsmouth in FA Cup third round |date=5 January 2019 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> Despite his lack of game time, Hanley remained club captain as Norwich gained promotion to the [[Premier League]]. In the final game of the season, as Norwich defeated [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 2\u20131, winning the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] title, Hanley was brought on as an 89th minute substitute for [[Onel Hernandez]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48081773 |title=Aston Villa 1-2 Norwich City: Canaries win to seal Championship title |date=5 May 2019 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> and lifted the Championship trophy alongside team captain Zimmermann.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/47713270 |title=Relieve the final day of the Championship season as it happened |date=5 May 2019 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref><ref name=trophymedal19>{{Cite news |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2834759-championship-table-2019-football-results-final-standings-and-play-off-fixtures |title=Championship Table 2019: Football Results, Final Standings and Play-Off Fixtures |website=Bleacher Report |date=5 May 2019 |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019&ndash;20====\nHanley scored an [[own goal]] in a 4&ndash;1 defeat against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 9 August, which was the first goal of the [[2019&ndash;20 Premier League]] season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49201578 |title=Liverpool 4&ndash;1 Norwich City |first=Neil |last=Johnston |website=BBC Sport |date=9 August 2019 |accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nHanley captained [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland at under-19 level]].<ref name=NewCH/> On 17 November 2010, he played for [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21s]] when aged 18 in a 3\u20131 win against [[Northern Ireland national under-21 football team|Northern Ireland]] at [[Firhill]].<ref>[http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=128&newsCategoryID=6&newsID=6832 Under-21s defeat Northern Ireland] Scottish Football Association, 17 November 2010</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2011, Hanley was called up to the [[Scotland national football team|senior Scotland squad]] for the first time ahead of the game against [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] in the [[Nations Cup (football)|Nations Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/scotland/9383384.stm |website=BBC Sport |title=Hanley nets first Scots call-up |date=1 February 2011}}</ref> He made his full international debut as an 84th-minute substitute on 25 May 2011 coming on for [[Gary Caldwell]] against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] in the Nations Cup in [[Dublin]].<ref name=qosintl>[http://qosfc.com/new_newsview.aspx?newsid=674 Doonhamer internationalists] Queen of the South F.C., 25 May 2011</ref> His first Scotland goal was in his fifth full international when he opened the scoring in a [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualifier]] at home against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] on 22 March 2013 at [[Hampden Park]].<ref name=Wales/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n[[File:Grant Hanley (cropped).jpg|thumb|200px|Hanley playing for [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in 2014]]\n\n{{updated|match played 25 January 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=8|[[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n|[[2009\u201310 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2009\u201310]]<ref name=\"Games played by Grant Hanley in 2009/2010\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2009|name=Grant Hanley|access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|1||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref name=\"Games played by Grant Hanley in 2010/2011\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2010|name=Grant Hanley|access-date=29 September 2015}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|7||1||2||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||9||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref name=\"Games played by Grant Hanley in 2011/2012\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2011|name=Grant Hanley|access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|23||1||1||0||4||0||colspan=2|\u2014||28||1\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref name=\"Games played by Grant Hanley in 2012/2013\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2012|name=Grant Hanley|access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref>\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|39||2||5||1||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||45||3\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"Games played by Grant Hanley in 2013/2014\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2013|name=Grant Hanley|access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|38||1||2||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||40||1\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2014\u201315]]<ref name=\"Games played by Grant Hanley in 2014/2015\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2014|name=Grant Hanley|access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|31||1||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||31||1\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=\"Games played by Grant Hanley in 2015/2016\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2015|name=Grant Hanley|access-date=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|44||2||2||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||46||2\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!183!!8!!12!!1!!5!!0!!colspan=2|\u2014!!200!!9\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Newcastle United F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"Games played by Grant Hanley in 2016/2017\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2016|name=Grant Hanley|access-date=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|10||1||3||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||16||1\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Newcastle United F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"GH17\"/>\n|Premier League\n|0||0||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!10!!1!!3!!0!!4!!0!!colspan=2|\u2014!!17!!1\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Norwich City F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"GH17\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2017|accessdate=10 October 2017}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|32||1||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||34||1\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Norwich City F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"GH18\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2018|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|9||1||1||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||10||1\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Norwich City F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"GH19\">{{Soccerbase season|54555|2019|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|10||0||2||1||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||12||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!51!!2!!5!!1!!0!!0!!colspan=2|\u2014!!56!!3\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!244!!11!!20!!2!!9!!0!!colspan=2|\u2014!!273!!13\n|}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|match played 4 September 2017}}<ref name=\"NFT\"/>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=7|[[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n|2011||3||0\n|-\n|2012||1||0\n|-\n|2013||8||1\n|-\n|2014||5||0\n|-\n|2015||3||0\n|-\n|2016||7||0\n|-\n|2017||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!28!!1\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''As of match played 29 May 2016. Scotland score listed first, score column indicates score after each Hanley goal.''<ref name=NFT>{{NFT player |id=41802 |name=Hanley, Grant |accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ International goals by date, venue, cap, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!scope=col|No.\n!scope=col|Date\n!scope=col|Venue\n!scope=col|Cap\n!scope=col|Opponent\n!scope=col|Score\n!scope=col|Result\n!scope=col|Competition\n!scope=col|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=row|1\n|22 March 2013||[[Hampden Park]], [[Glasgow]], Scotland||5||{{fb|Wales}}||1\u20130||1\u20132||[[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group A|2014 FIFA World Cup qualification]]||<ref name=Wales>{{cite news |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |title=Scotland 1\u20132 Wales |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21653797 |website=BBC Sport |date=22 March 2013 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Newcastle United'''\n*[[EFL Championship]]: [[2016\u201317 EFL Championship|2016\u201317]]<ref>{{cite book |editor-first=John |editor-last=Anderson |title=Sky Sports Football Yearbook 2017\u20132018 |year=2017 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-1-4722-3397-4 |pages=254\u2013255}}</ref>\n\n'''Norwich City'''\n*EFL Championship: [[2018\u201319 EFL Championship|2018\u201319]]<ref name=trophymedal19/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160701190401/http://www.rovers.co.uk/team/player-profile/grant-hanley/5 Grant Hanley profile] at the Blackburn Rovers F.C. website\n*[https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/players/?pid=164188 Grant Hanley profile] at the Scottish Football Association website\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Blackburn Rovers F.C. Player of the Season}}\n{{Norwich City F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hanley, Grant}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dumfries]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Norwich City F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Grant Hanley\n| image = Grant Hanley 2018.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Hanley playing for [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in 2018\n| fullname = Grant Campbell Hanley<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|23322|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|11|20|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman/>\n| birth_place = [[Dumfries]], Scotland\n| height = {{convert|1.87|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rovers.co.uk/team/player-profile/index.aspx?playerid=417715&tcmuri=96232 |title=Player Profile \u2013 Grant Hanley |accessdate=15 March 2011 |publisher=Blackburn Rovers F.C.}}</ref>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n| clubnumber = 5\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n| youthyears2 = 2004\u20132006\n| youthclubs2 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n| youthyears3 = 2006\u20132008\n| youthclubs3 = [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]\n| youthyears4 = 2008\u20132010\n| youthclubs4 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n| years1 = 2010\u20132016\n| clubs1 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n| caps1 = 183\n| goals1 = 8\n| years2 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs2 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n| caps2 = 10\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs3 = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n| caps3 = 51\n| goals3 = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 2010\u20132011\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2010\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2011\u2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 29\n| nationalgoals3 = 1\n| club-update = 21:35, 22 January 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 30 June 2018 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Grant Campbell Hanley''' (born 20 November 1991) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defender (association football)|defender]] for {{English football updater|NorwichC}} club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]. He has previously played for [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].\n\n==Early years==\nHanley was born in [[Dumfries]], [[Dumfries and Galloway]].<ref name=Hugman/> He was involved at youth level with local club [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]], [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] and with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] before he joined [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] as a 16-year-old in 2008.<ref>[http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news/article/muirheads-career-built-on-solid-bricks/ Muirhead's career built on solid bricks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616125249/http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news/article/muirheads-career-built-on-solid-bricks/ |date=16 June 2012 }} Scottish Football League, 14 January 2011</ref><ref name=NewCH>[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/scotland/2010/05/24/i-can-be-the-new-colin-hendry-for-scotland-blackburn-vows-scots-under-19-skipper-grant-hanley-86908-22281189/ I can be the new Colin Hendry for Scotland & Blackburn, vows Scots under 19 skipper Grant Hanley] ''Daily Record'', 24 May 2010</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Blackburn Rovers===\nAt Rovers, Hanley was captain of the under-18 team.<ref name=NewCH/> Hanley made his [[Premier League]] debut for Rovers in a 1\u20130 win at Aston Villa on 9 May 2010.<ref name=BRProf>{{cite web |title=Grant Hanley first team profile |url=http://www.rovers.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10303~51151,00.html |publisher=Blackburn Rovers F.C. |accessdate=10 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505200558/http://www.rovers.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10303~51151%2C00.html |archivedate=5 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com//football/match_facts/0,,11065_3151896,00+en-USS_01DBC.html |title=Aston Villa 0 \u2013 1 Blackburn |website=Sky Sports |date=9 May 2010 |accessdate=9 May 2010}}</ref> Hanley committed his future when he signed a new five-year deal with Blackburn on 21 July 2010.<ref>[http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/sport/8284970.Blackburn_Rovers_defender_Hanley_pens_five_year_contract/ Blackburn Rovers defender Hanley pens five-year contract] ''Lancashire Telegraph'', 22 July 2010</ref>\n\nHanley made his first Premier League appearance of season 2010\u201311 as a 67th-minute substitute in a 1\u20131 draw at home to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} He made his [[FA Cup]] debut on 8 January 2011, against [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in a 1\u20130 victory at Ewood Park.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/match/2011/jan/08/blackburn-v-qpr Blackburn Rovers v QPR Match facts] ''The Guardian'', 8 January 2011</ref> On 5 March 2011, Hanley scored his first goal for Rovers in a 3\u20132 defeat against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] at [[Craven Cottage]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9411020.stm Fulham 3\u20132 Blackburn] ''BBC Sport'', 5 March 2011</ref> That was the last of his nine Blackburn first team appearances that season although he was to make his international debut at the end of the season.<ref name=qosintl/> On 31 December 2011, Hanley started and scored the winning goal in a 3\u20132 win against local rivals [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16373420.stm Match winner Grant Hanley hails Blackburn Rovers youth] ''BBC Sport'', 31 December 2011</ref><ref>[http://football.uk.reuters.com/leagues/premiership/news/2011/12/31/489C36A6-33D7-11E1-AC36-1AE57F33923B.php Blackburn stun United, Spurs and Chelsea slip up] Reuters, 31 December 2011</ref> This win lifted Blackburn off the bottom of the table.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/16324998.stm Man Utd 2\u20133 Blackburn] ''BBC Sport'', 31 December 2011</ref> On 14 April 2012, in a Premier League fixture against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] at the [[Liberty Stadium]], he suffered ankle ligament damage.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Hanley made 28 appearances and scored one goal in all competitions for Rovers but the club was relegated into the [[Football League Championship|Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/matchday/league-table.html |title=Premier League Table |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2012\u201313 season Hanley maintained his first team place and formed a [[2012\u201313 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season#Appearances and goals|partnership]] with [[Scott Dann]]. At the end of the season, he signed a five-year contract with the club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Transfer news: Blackburn give Grant Hanley long-term contract at Ewood Park |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12691/8754287/Transfer-news-Blackburn-give-Grant-Hanley-long-term-contract-at-Ewood-Park |website=Sky Sports |date=4 June 2013 |accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter Dann left for [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in January 2014, Hanley was appointed as the new [[Captain (association football)|captain]] of the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delighted for the captain |url=http://www.rovers.co.uk/news/article/delighted-for-the-captain-1336772.aspx |publisher=Blackburn Rovers F.C. |date=3 February 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\nOn 21 July 2016, Hanley signed for newly relegated Championship club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on a five-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news |title=Grant Hanley: Newcastle United sign Blackburn Rovers captain |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36857862 |website=BBC Sport |date=21 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> He was handed the number 5 shirt, previously worn by [[Georginio Wijnaldum]].\nHe scored his first goal for the club in the 79th minute in a 6\u20130 win versus [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at [[Loftus Road]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37282510 |title=Queens Park Rangers 0-6 Newcastle United |date=14 September 2016 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Norwich City===\n====2017&ndash;18====\nOn 30 August 2017, Hanley joined [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] on a four-year deal for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{citenews|title=Grant Hanley joins Norwich City|url=https://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2017/august/grant-hanley-joins-norwich-city/|publisher=Norwich City F.C.|date=30 August 2017}}</ref> He made his debut on 9 September 2017, coming on as a substitute in a 1\u20130 win over [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] at [[Carrow Road]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41132799 |title=Norwich City 1-0 Birmingham City |date=9 September 2017 |website=BBC Sport|access-date=9 September 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref> Although he had been something of an emergency buy, with Norwich having started the season with a number of injuries and playing inexperienced centre backs, Hanley soon became a regular in the team, often being deployed as one of three centre halves with [[Timm Klose]] and [[Christoph Zimmermann]]. He ultimately made 32 league appearances for Norwich during the 2017\u201318 season, plus two in the FA Cup. One of his most memorable contributions came in the derby game against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on 18 February. Ipswich had gone 1\u20130 up in the 89th minute and seemed set for a first win over Norwich in nine years. However, deep into added time, Hanley chased a ball to the byline and crossed it back into the goal area, allowing Klose to head it home for an equaliser.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43020998 |title=Norwich City 1-1 Ipswich Town |date=18 February 2018 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 January 2019 }}</ref> The following month, on 17 March, Hanley scored his first goal for Norwich, the second in a 3\u20132 win over [[Reading F.C.|Reading]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43353592 |title=Norwich City 3-2 Reading |date=17 March 2018 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n====2018&ndash;19====\nAt the beginning of the 2018&ndash;19 season, with [[Russell Martin (footballer)|Russell Martin]] leaving the club, Hanley was appointed Norwich's new club captain<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2018/august/grant-hanley-birmingham/ |title=Grant Hanley: Being named captain is a huge honour |date=1 August 2018 |publisher=Norwich City F.C. |accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> ahead of [[Ivo Pinto]], who had deputised for Martin for much of the previous season. He played in Norwich's opening six league games, getting his second goal for the club in a 4\u20133 defeat against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]];<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45066581 |title=Norwich City 3-4 West Bromwich Albion: Jay Rodriguez efforts please Baggies boss |date=11 August 2018 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> however, he was then injured in training.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45522509 |title=Grant Hanley: Norwich defender out for six weeks with quad injury |date=14 September 2018 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> During his absence, Klose and Zimmermann established themselves at centre-back, with [[Ben Godfrey]] also becoming a regular choice, and Hanley was restricted to a few appearances as substitute on his return. When he finally started a game, an [[FA Cup]] tie against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], he was sent off in the first fifteen minutes for a professional foul on [[Ronan Curtis]] and Norwich went on to lose 1\u20130.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46707005 |title=Norwich City 0-1 Portsmouth in FA Cup third round |date=5 January 2019 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> Despite his lack of game time, Hanley remained club captain as Norwich gained promotion to the [[Premier League]]. In the final game of the season, as Norwich defeated [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 2\u20131, winning the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] title, Hanley was brought on as an 89th minute substitute for [[Onel Hernandez]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48081773 |title=Aston Villa 1-2 Norwich City: Canaries win to seal Championship title |date=5 May 2019 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref> and lifted the Championship trophy alongside team captain Zimmermann.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/47713270 |title=Relieve the final day of the Championship season as it happened |date=5 May 2019 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 May 2019 }}</ref><ref name=trophymedal19>{{Cite news |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2834759-championship-table-2019-football-results-final-standings-and-play-off-fixtures |title=Championship Table 2019: Football Results, Final Standings and Play-Off Fixtures |website=Bleacher Report |date=5 May 2019 |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019&ndash;20====\nHanley scored an [[own goal]] in a 4&ndash;1 defeat against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 9 August, which was the first goal of the [[2019&ndash;20 Premier League]] season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49201578 |title=Liverpool 4&ndash;1 Norwich City |first=Neil |last=Johnston |website=BBC Sport |date=9 August 2019 |accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nHanley captained [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland at under-19 level]].<ref name=NewCH/> On 17 November 2010, he played for [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21s]] when aged 18 in a 3\u20131 win against [[Northern Ireland national under-21 football team|Northern Ireland]] at [[Firhill]].<ref>[http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=128&newsCategoryID=6&newsID=6832 Under-21s defeat Northern Ireland] Scottish Football Association, 17 November 2010</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2011, Hanley was called up to the [[Scotland national football team|senior Scotland squad]] for the first time ahead of the game against [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] in the [[Nations Cup (football)|Nations Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/scotland/9383384.stm |website=BBC Sport |title=Hanley nets first Scots call-up |date=1 February 2011}}</ref> He made his full international debut as an 84th-minute substitute on 25 May 2011 coming on for [[Gary Caldwell]] against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] in the Nations Cup in [[Dublin]].<ref name=qosintl>[http://qosfc.com/new_newsview.aspx?newsid=674 Doonhamer internationalists] Queen of the South F.C., 25 May 2011</ref> His first Scotland goal was in his fifth full international when he opened the scoring in a [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualifier]] at home against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] on 22 March 2013 at [[Hampden Park]].<ref name=Wales/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n[[File:Grant Hanley (cropped).jpg|thumb|200px|Hanley playing for [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in 2014]]\n\n{{updated|match played 25 January 2020}}\n\n{| 