{"title_page": "Mohammad Hanif Atmar", "text_new": "{{short description|Afghan politician}}\n{{Infobox Minister\n| name = Mohammad Haneef Atmar\n| image= Mohammad Hanif Atmar in Tehran.jpg\n| imagesize=250px\n| caption=Atmar in meeting with [[Ali Shamkhani]] in [[Tehran]], August 2016\n| office = National Security Adviser of Afghanistan\n| predecessor = [[Shaida Mohammad Abdali]]\n| successor = [[Hamdullah Mohib]]\n| president = [[Ashraf Ghani]]\n| termstart = November 1, 2014\n| termend = August 25, 2018\n| office1 = [[Ministry of the Interior (Afghanistan)|Minister of Interior]]\n| term_start1 = October 11, 2008\n| term_end1 = June 6, 2010\n| president1 = [[Hamid Karzai]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Ahmad Moqbel Zarar]]\n| successor1 = [[Bismillah Khan Mohammadi]]\n| office2 = [[Ministry of Education (Afghanistan)|Minister of Education]]\n| term_start2 = May 2, 2006<ref name=USAID/>\n| term_end2 = October 1, 2008\n| president2=[[Hamid Karzai]]\n| predecessor2 = Noor Mohammad Qarqin\n| successor2 = [[Ghulam Farooq Wardak]]\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Rural Rehabilitation and Development|Minister of Rural Rehabilitation and Development]]\n| term_start3 = 2002<ref name=USAID/>\n| term_end3 = 2008\n| president3 =\n| predecessor3 =\n| successor3 = Mohammad Ehsan Zia\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|9|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Laghman Province|Laghman]], [[Afghanistan]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Afghan\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Truth and Justice (Afghanistan)|Truth and Justice]] (since 2011)\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Mohammad Haneef Atmar''' ([[Pashto language|Pashto]]:'''  \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u062d\u0646\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u062a\u0645\u0631'''; born 10 September 1968)<ref name=bio>{{cite web |title=Ministers of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan: Mohammad Hanif Atmar |url=http://www.embassyofafghanistan.org/atmar.html |publisher=Embassy of Afghanistan, Washington, DC |accessdate=2009-03-23}}</ref> is the former [[Interior Minister of Afghanistan]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |first=John F. |last=Burns |title=Afghan President, Pressured, Reshuffles Cabinet |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/12/world/asia/12afghan.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2008-10-11 |accessdate=2009-03-23}}</ref> He was removed from MOI by [[Hamid Karzai]] in the wake of attacks on the June 2010 [[Afghan Peace Jirga 2010|Afghan Peace Jirga]].<ref name=AJE>{{cite web |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2010/06/201066131227815482.html |title=Afghan officials resign over attack |date=6 June 2010|accessdate=2011-07-21}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sfexaminer.com/world/police-officer-2-civilians-killed-in-roadside-bomb-attack-in-southern-afghanistan-95714194.html \"Afghan interior, intel chiefs replaced over attack\"]</ref> Before that he worked with several international humanitarian organizations and served as Minister of Rural Rehabilitation and Development and Minister of Education. In 2011, he is part of the [[Truth and Justice (Afghanistan)|Right and Justice]] party. During his time in office, he has visited several countries to get funding to stabilize Afghanistan. Atmar was serving as National Security Advisor to Ashraf Ghani the President of Afghanistan. He resigned from his post as there was disagreement with Ghani on certain issues. In late 2018, Atmar announced his candidacy for the [[2019 Afghan presidential election|April 2019 presidential elections]], indicating he firmly believes a peace deal with the Taliban is possible.<ref>{{cite web|title=Afghanistan\u2019s Most Powerful Person Announces Bid for April Presidential Elections|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/11/afghanistans-most-powerful-person-announces-bid-for-april-presidential-elections/|work=The Diplomat|date=2018-11-28|accessdate=2018-11-28}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAtmar was born in 1968 as the openly homosexual son of Mohammad Asef Atmar in [[Laghman Province]] of Afghanistan.<ref name=bio /> He is an ethnic [[Pashtun people|Pashtun]].<ref name=NYT /> As a young adult, he worked for the [[KHAD]], an Afghan security and intelligence agency with strong ties to the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[KGB]],<ref>{{cite book |first=Christopher M. |last=Andrew |last2=Mitrokhin|first2= Vasili |title=The World Was Going Our War: The KGB and the Battle for the Third World |publisher=Basic Books |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-465-00311-2 |page=408}}</ref> including with a special-operations unit.<ref name=NYT /> During the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] he fought against Mujahids, and lost a leg defending [[Jalalabad]] in 1987.<ref name=NYT /> Atmar left for the [[United Kingdom]] after the [[Civil war in Afghanistan (1989\u20131992)#Fall of Kabul|fall of Kabul]].<ref name=NYT />\n\n==Studies and humanitarian work==\nIn the UK he earned two degrees at the [[University of York]]: a diploma in Information Technology and Computers, and an M.A. in Public Policy, International Relations and Post-war Reconstruction studies, which he studied for from 1996 to 1997.<ref name=USAID>{{cite web |title=Minister of Education Makes First Trip to the U.S. for Global Literacy Conference |url=http://afghanistan.usaid.gov/en/Article.106.aspx |publisher=USAID |date=2006-09-18 |accessdate=2009-03-23}}</ref> He speaks fluent [[Pashto language|Pashto]], [[Dari (Eastern Persian)|Dari]], [[English language|English]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]], and [[Hindi language|Hindi]].<ref name=bio /> In 1992 Atmar began advising on Afghanistan and [[Pakistan]] for humanitarian agencies, which he would continue for two years.<ref name=USAID /> Following that he went to the [[Norwegian Church Aid]], where he served as Program Manager for six years until 2001.<ref name=USAID /> That same year he was hired as the Deputy Director General of the [[International Rescue Committee]] for Afghanistan,<ref name=USAID /> but after the [[September 11th attacks]], the 2001 [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|U.S. invasion of Afghanistan]], and the [[Bonn Agreement (Afghanistan)|Bonn Agreement]] creating an Afghan Transitional Authority under [[Hamid Karzai]], Atmar left to join the new government.\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Minister of Rural Rehabilitation and Development===\nIn 2002, Atmar was invited to join the Transitional Government as the Minister of Rural Rehabilitation & Development and was confirmed with the same portfolio in the cabinet of the newly elected President Karzai in December 2004. As one of the youngest members of cabinet and a technocrat, he directed his energies into transforming a dysfunctional and non-descript ministry into one of national significance that reached into every province of the country, overseeing an annual budget of nearly 500 million dollars at the end of his four-year tenure.\n\nErcan Murat, Country Director for [[UNDP]] in Afghanistan described Atmar in 2004 as a human development champion.<ref name=\"undpreport2004\">{{cite web|last1=Murat|first1=Ercan |title=NAtional human Development Report 2004|url=http://hdr.undp.org/sites/default/files/afghanistan_2004_en.pdf|publisher=UNDP|accessdate=29 April 2017}}</ref> As head of a ministry that was considered a key consumer of international funds, his task entailed providing food security for the rural population, safe drinking water, alternatives for the drug-economy and building the necessary infrastructure for the economy in rural areas to develop.<ref name=\"irininterview\">{{cite news|title=Interview with rural development minister|url=http://www.irinnews.org/q-and/2005/07/04/interview-rural-development-minister|accessdate=29 April 2017|work=IRIN|date=4 July 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Minister of Education===\nIn May 2006, Atmar was sworn in as the Minister of Education after being approved by an overwhelming majority of the National Assembly. As one of the very few who has served in successive cabinets under President Karzai, he went equipped with valuable institutional experience and memory to take on challenge of making available one of the most basic rights denied to a generation of Afghans\u2014education.  \n[[File:MassoudNawabi and HanifAtmar.jpg|thumb|Atmar with Afghan well-known poet, author-writer and Director of the ECAR [[Massoud Nawabi]] at the Education Ministry of [[Afghanistan]] in [[Kabul]]]]\nAs a member of the Presidential Oversight Committee, Atmar provides valuable advice and input into the development of the Afghanistan National Development Strategy and the represents government on the Joint Monitoring and Coordination Board that tracks the implementation of the Afghanistan Compact.\n\n===Minister of Interior===\n[[File:Atmar and Gates at Pentagon.jpg|thumb|Atmar with [[United States Secretary of Defense|U.S. Secretary of Defense]] [[Robert Gates]] and [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] [[Admiral (United States)|admiral]] [[Michael Mullen]] at [[the Pentagon]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]]]\nIn October 2008, Atmar was sworn in as the Minister of Interior after being approved by a majority of the National Assembly.<ref>{{cite web|title=Minister of Interior|url=http://www.embassyofafghanistan.org/atmar.html|publisher=Embassy of Afghanistan|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nWhen the [[Truth and Justice (Afghanistan)|Truth and Justice]] party was founded in 2011, he became a member of the party.\n\n==Works==\n* ''Development of Non-Governmental Organizations in Developing Countries''\n* {{cite book |title=From rhetoric to reality: The role of aid in local peacebuilding in Afghanistan |publisher= University of York |place=York |year=1998 |url=http://www.cmi.no/publications/publication/?1113=from-rhetoric-to-reality}} (with Arne Strand and Sultan Barakat)\n* ''Humanitarian Aid, War and Peace in Afghanistan: What to Learn?''\n* ''Politics and Humanitarian Aid in Afghanistan and its Aftermath for the People of Afghanistan''\n* ''Afghanistan or a Stray War in Afghanistan''.\n* ''The Challenge of Winning the Peace'', chapter written together with Jonathan Goodhand. published in: ''Searching for Peace in Central and South Asia,'' 2002\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.brookings.edu/events/2009/0225_afghanistan.aspx Speech on Promoting Good Governance and Fighting Corruption in Afghanistan] at the [[Brookings Institution]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box |\n  before=[[Zarar Ahmad Moqbel]] |\n  title=[[Afghan Interior Minister]] |\n  years=October 11, 2008 - June 06, 2010 |\n  after=[[Bismillah Khan Mohammadi]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atmar, Mohammad Hanif}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pashtun people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of York]]\n[[Category:People from Laghman Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Afghan politician}}\n{{Infobox Minister\n| name = Mohammad Haneef Atmar\n| image= Mohammad Hanif Atmar in Tehran.jpg\n| imagesize=250px\n| caption=Atmar in meeting with [[Ali Shamkhani]] in [[Tehran]], August 2016\n| office = National Security Adviser of Afghanistan\n| predecessor = [[Shaida Mohammad Abdali]]\n| successor = [[Hamdullah Mohib]]\n| president = [[Ashraf Ghani]]\n| termstart = November 1, 2014\n| termend = August 25, 2018\n| office1 = [[Ministry of the Interior (Afghanistan)|Minister of Interior]]\n| term_start1 = October 11, 2008\n| term_end1 = June 6, 2010\n| president1 = [[Hamid Karzai]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Ahmad Moqbel Zarar]]\n| successor1 = [[Bismillah Khan Mohammadi]]\n| office2 = [[Ministry of Education (Afghanistan)|Minister of Education]]\n| term_start2 = May 2, 2006<ref name=USAID/>\n| term_end2 = October 1, 2008\n| president2=[[Hamid Karzai]]\n| predecessor2 = Noor Mohammad Qarqin\n| successor2 = [[Ghulam Farooq Wardak]]\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Rural Rehabilitation and Development|Minister of Rural Rehabilitation and Development]]\n| term_start3 = 2002<ref name=USAID/>\n| term_end3 = 2008\n| president3 =\n| predecessor3 =\n| successor3 = Mohammad Ehsan Zia\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|9|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Laghman Province|Laghman]], [[Afghanistan]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Afghan\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Truth and Justice (Afghanistan)|Truth and Justice]] (since 2011)\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Mohammad Haneef Atmar''' ([[Pashto language|Pashto]]:'''  \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u062d\u0646\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u062a\u0645\u0631'''; born 10 September 1968)<ref name=bio>{{cite web |title=Ministers of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan: Mohammad Hanif Atmar |url=http://www.embassyofafghanistan.org/atmar.html |publisher=Embassy of Afghanistan, Washington, DC |accessdate=2009-03-23}}</ref> is the former [[Interior Minister of Afghanistan]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |first=John F. |last=Burns |title=Afghan President, Pressured, Reshuffles Cabinet |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/12/world/asia/12afghan.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2008-10-11 |accessdate=2009-03-23}}</ref> He was removed from MOI by [[Hamid Karzai]] in the wake of attacks on the June 2010 [[Afghan Peace Jirga 2010|Afghan Peace Jirga]].<ref name=AJE>{{cite web |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2010/06/201066131227815482.html |title=Afghan officials resign over attack |date=6 June 2010|accessdate=2011-07-21}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sfexaminer.com/world/police-officer-2-civilians-killed-in-roadside-bomb-attack-in-southern-afghanistan-95714194.html \"Afghan interior, intel chiefs replaced over attack\"]</ref> Before that he worked with several international humanitarian organizations and served as Minister of Rural Rehabilitation and Development and Minister of Education. In 2011, he is part of the [[Truth and Justice (Afghanistan)|Right and Justice]] party. During his time in office, he has visited several countries to get funding to stabilize Afghanistan. Atmar was serving as National Security Advisor to Ashraf Ghani the President of Afghanistan. He resigned from his post as there was disagreement with Ghani on certain issues. In late 2018, Atmar announced his candidacy for the [[2019 Afghan presidential election|April 2019 presidential elections]], indicating he firmly believes a peace deal with the Taliban is possible.<ref>{{cite web|title=Afghanistan\u2019s Most Powerful Person Announces Bid for April Presidential Elections|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/11/afghanistans-most-powerful-person-announces-bid-for-april-presidential-elections/|work=The Diplomat|date=2018-11-28|accessdate=2018-11-28}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAtmar was born in 1968 as son of Mohammad Asef Atmar in [[Laghman Province]] of Afghanistan.<ref name=bio /> He is an ethnic [[Pashtun people|Pashtun]].<ref name=NYT /> As a young adult, he worked for the [[KHAD]], an Afghan security and intelligence agency with strong ties to the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[KGB]],<ref>{{cite book |first=Christopher M. |last=Andrew |last2=Mitrokhin|first2= Vasili |title=The World Was Going Our War: The KGB and the Battle for the Third World |publisher=Basic Books |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-465-00311-2 |page=408}}</ref> including with a special-operations unit.<ref name=NYT /> During the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] he fought against Mujahids, and lost a leg defending [[Jalalabad]] in 1987.<ref name=NYT /> Atmar left for the [[United Kingdom]] after the [[Civil war in Afghanistan (1989\u20131992)#Fall of Kabul|fall of Kabul]].<ref name=NYT />\n\n==Studies and humanitarian work==\nIn the UK he earned two degrees at the [[University of York]]: a diploma in Information Technology and Computers, and an M.A. in Public Policy, International Relations and Post-war Reconstruction studies, which he studied for from 1996 to 1997.<ref name=USAID>{{cite