fghanistan_2004_en.pdf|publisher=UNDP|accessdate=29 April 2017}}</ref> As head of a ministry that was considered a key consumer of international funds, his task entailed providing food security for the rural population, safe drinking water, alternatives for the drug-economy and building the necessary infrastructure for the economy in rural areas to develop.<ref name=\"irininterview\">{{cite news|title=Interview with rural development minister|url=http://www.irinnews.org/q-and/2005/07/04/interview-rural-development-minister|accessdate=29 April 2017|work=IRIN|date=4 July 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Minister of Education===\nIn May 2006, Atmar was sworn in as the Minister of Education after being approved by an overwhelming majority of the National Assembly. As one of the very few who has served in successive cabinets under President Karzai, he went equipped with valuable institutional experience and memory to take on challenge of making available one of the most basic rights denied to a generation of Afghans\u2014education.  \n[[File:MassoudNawabi and HanifAtmar.jpg|thumb|Atmar with Afghan well-known poet, author-writer and Director of the ECAR [[Massoud Nawabi]] at the Education Ministry of [[Afghanistan]] in [[Kabul]]]]\nAs a member of the Presidential Oversight Committee, Atmar provides valuable advice and input into the development of the Afghanistan National Development Strategy and the represents government on the Joint Monitoring and Coordination Board that tracks the implementation of the Afghanistan Compact.\n\n===Minister of Interior===\n[[File:Atmar and Gates at Pentagon.jpg|thumb|Atmar with [[United States Secretary of Defense|U.S. Secretary of Defense]] [[Robert Gates]] and [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] [[Admiral (United States)|admiral]] [[Michael Mullen]] at [[the Pentagon]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]]]\nIn October 2008, Atmar was sworn in as the Minister of Interior after being approved by a majority of the National Assembly.<ref>{{cite web|title=Minister of Interior|url=http://www.embassyofafghanistan.org/atmar.html|publisher=Embassy of Afghanistan|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nWhen the [[Truth and Justice (Afghanistan)|Truth and Justice]] party was founded in 2011, he became a member of the party.\n\n==Works==\n* ''Development of Non-Governmental Organizations in Developing Countries''\n* {{cite book |title=From rhetoric to reality: The role of aid in local peacebuilding in Afghanistan |publisher= University of York |place=York |year=1998 |url=http://www.cmi.no/publications/publication/?1113=from-rhetoric-to-reality}} (with Arne Strand and Sultan Barakat)\n* ''Humanitarian Aid, War and Peace in Afghanistan: What to Learn?''\n* ''Politics and Humanitarian Aid in Afghanistan and its Aftermath for the People of Afghanistan''\n* ''Afghanistan or a Stray War in Afghanistan''.\n* ''The Challenge of Winning the Peace'', chapter written together with Jonathan Goodhand. published in: ''Searching for Peace in Central and South Asia,'' 2002\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.brookings.edu/events/2009/0225_afghanistan.aspx Speech on Promoting Good Governance and Fighting Corruption in Afghanistan] at the [[Brookings Institution]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box |\n  before=[[Zarar Ahmad Moqbel]] |\n  title=[[Afghan Interior Minister]] |\n  years=October 11, 2008 - June 06, 2010 |\n  after=[[Bismillah Khan Mohammadi]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atmar, Mohammad Hanif}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pashtun people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of York]]\n[[Category:People from Laghman Province]]\n", "name_user": "94.58.173.253", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life:Typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohammad_Hanif_Atmar"}
{"title_page": "Scrabo Tower", "text_new": "{{short description|19th century folly in Northern Ireland}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{infobox historic site\n|name=Scrabo Tower\n|image=CIMG1495 ScraboHorizView.JPG\n|alt=Photograph of the tower against a blue sky with white clouds\n|caption=Scrabo Tower, May 2007\n|locmapin=UK Northern Ireland\n|map_caption=Location in Northern Ireland\n|coordinates={{coord|54.58010|-5.7155|type:landmark_scale:5000|display=title,inline}}\n|built=1857-1859\n|architect=Lanyon & Lynn\n|designation1=Grade B+ listed building\n|designation1_date=1977\n|designation1_number=HB24/11/031\n}}\n'''Scraba Tar''' is a {{convert|135|ft}} high 19th-century lookout tower or folly that stands on Scrabo Hill near [[Newtownards]] in [[County Down]], [[Northern Ireland]]. It provides wide views and you can see Donaghadee Road and the carry out easily. Popular with doggers and for car park shenanigans. It was built as a memorial to [[Charles Vane, 3rd Marquess of Londonderry]] and was originally known as the '''Londonderry Monument'''. Its architectural style is [[Scottish baronial architecture#Scottish Baronial Revival|Scottish Baronial Revival]].{{harv|Howley|1993}}\n\n== Name and location ==\nNowadays, the tower on Scrabo Hill is usually just called Scrabo Tower and is visited for its views and surroundings. However, its original name was Londonderry Monument or Memorial. That name referred to the [[Marquess of Londonderry|Marquesses of Londonderry]] and only indirectly to the town or county of that name, which is {{convert|87|miles|km}} away. The marquesses owned much ground around the hill. The hill and tower rise over the town of [[Newtownards]], {{convert|10|mi|km}} east of Belfast. As the tower dominates the town, it is often used as an emblem for Newtownards. The tower is built on the site of a prehistoric hill fort.{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031a]|ps=: \"During the Bronze Age the summit of Scrabo Hill was the site of a considerable settlement, enclosed within an oval hill fort.\"}}{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124a|ps=: \"The excavations for the foundations disclosed a vast quantity of wild boar tusks and bones, suggesting that the elevated position had been formerly the scene of Druidical sacrifices or of pre-historic pic-nics.\"}} Scrabo is pronounced {{IPAc-en|'|s|k|r|\u00e6|b|ou}} according to the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC){{sfn|Pointon|1990|p=[https://archive.org/details/bbcpronouncingdi00gepo/page/217 217] |ps=: \"skr\u00e6bo\u028a\"}} or {{IPA-sco|\u02c8skr\u0251\u02d0bo|}} according to the pronunciation heard on the ''[[Placenames Database of Ireland]]'' website.<ref name=DCU>{{cite web |url=https://www.logainm.ie/en/1413295 |title=The Placenames Database of Ireland |publisher=Dublin City University |accessdate=1 September 2018}}</ref> The pronunciation of the final vowel as the pure sound [o] rather than the diphthong [ou] is also attested by the spelling variation Scraboh.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124b|ps=: \"The Londonderry Monument, Scraboh Hill, Co Down\"}}\n\nTwo etymologies are proposed for Scrabo. The first derives the name from Irish ''screabach'' meaning \"rough stony land\".{{sfn|McKay|2007|p=129}} Screabach is also the Irish name of the Scrabo townland in which the hill lies.<ref name=DCU /> The second derives the name from Irish ''scraith b\u00f3'', which means \"sward of the cow\",<ref>[https://www.logainm.ie/en/ Placenames Database of Ireland]. Search for Scrabo. Then find the right archival document by clicking the Open Scanned Records Button. Note 'scraith b\u00f3' and 'sward of the cow'.</ref> \"cow pasture\",<ref name=Orme>{{cite web |last=Orme |first=Debby |url=http://scrabotower.com/scrabo-tower.html |title=The History of Scrabo Tower - Guardian of the North Down coast |accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> or \"sod of the cow\",{{sfn|Jones|1974|p=429}} as ''scraith'' means sward, sod or turf, whereas ''b\u00f3'' means cow. This derivation explains the final \"o\" of Scrabo.\n\n==History==\n===Origins===\nThe tower commemorates the [[Charles Vane, 3rd Marquess of Londonderry|3rd Marquess of Londonderry]], who was born Charles William Stewart in 1788. He fought in the Napoleonic Wars.{{sfn|Vane |1828}} He became married twice first Catherine Bligh and then [[Frances Vane, Marchioness of Londonderry|Frances Anne Vane]]. At his second wife was a rich heiress and the marriage contract obliged him to change his surname to hers, which explains why he was first called Stewart and later Vane. He succeeded his half-brother [[Viscount Castlereagh]] as marquess in 1822 and became owner of the family estate in County Down. The estate's great house, [[Mount Stewart]], became his Irish residence but after his second marriage he lived mostly in England.\n\nIn 1854, when the 3rd Marquess died, his eldest son, [[Frederick Stewart, 4th Marquess of Londonderry]], and his widow, the dowager marchioness, decided to build him a monument. As these two were not at good terms, each conceived and pushed his or her own project. Two monuments resulted: the Irish tower discussed here and an equestrian statue in Durham, England.{{sfn|Lloyd|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198614063/page/98 98]|ps=: \"an equestrian statue by him by Gaetano Monti was unveiled in the market-place at Durham by Disraeli on 2 December 1861.\"}}\n\nA committee was formed in Newtownards to raise funds by subscription for an Irish monument. The local gentry and the late marquess's friends, among which [[Napoleon III]] of France, donated most of the money, with some of the tenants also contributing.{{sfn|McCavery|1994|p=140a|ps=: \"Two thirds of the cost was raised by 98 individuals (the list was headed by the Emperor Napoleon III of France), most of whom were fellow gentry from Antrim and Down, and personal friends of the Marquess.\"}} Altogether 730 people subscribed.{{sfn|Illustrated London News|1857|p=299a|ps=: \"There was also placed in the jar a list of the subscribers' names, 730 of them all;\"}} The person behind these efforts was his eldest son [[Frederick Stewart, 4th Marquess of Londonderry]].{{sfn|Hyde|1979|p=50|ps=: \"At the same time her husband constructed the great tower on Scrabo Hill overlooking the town in his father's memory.\"}}\n\nThe funds raised allowed for a budget of \u00a32000. At first, the monument was to be built in Newtownards, but it was later shifted to Scrabo Hill where it could be seen from Mount Stewart and where suitable building stone was quarried. In December 1855 the committee decided to hold a design competition.{{sfn|McCavery|1994|p=140b|ps=: \"In 1855, it was decided that the memorial should be erected on Scrabo, and that the design should be subject of a competition with the cost of the work not to exceed \u00a32,000.\"}} The deadline was 1 February 1856.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archiseek.com/2011/1857-scrabo-tower-newtownards-co-down/#.U1k7q_ldVws |publisher=Archiseek |title=1857 \u2013 Scrabo Tower, Newtownards, Co. Down |quote=The architects designs were to be received before February 1, 1856 }}</ref> Four entries were considered: an obelisk and three towers. The first prize went to the obelisk, which was submitted by [[W. J. Barre|William Joseph Barre]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Co. Down, Scrabo Hill, Londonderry Monument |url=https://www.dia.ie/works/view/872/building/CO.+DOWN%2C+SCRABO+HILL%2C+LONDONDERRY+MONUMENT |website=Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940 |publisher=Irish Architectural Archive |accessdate=17 July 2018 |quote=Placed 1st in competition}}</ref> However, the obelisk came to nothing and indeed none of the first three projects was executed. When the committee called for tenders from building contractors, all the submissions for the three best-rated entries exceeded the budget and were therefore rejected. Finally, a tender by Hugh Dixon from Newtownards for the fourth project was accepted.<ref>{{cite web |title=Co. Down, Scrabo Hill, Londonderry Monument |url=https://www.dia.ie/works/view/872/building/CO.+DOWN%2C+SCRABO+HILL%2C+LONDONDERRY+MONUMENT |website=Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940 |publisher=Irish Architectural Archive |accessdate=17 July 2018 |quote=Contractor: Hugh Dixon, Newtownards}}</ref> However, supporters of William Barre claimed that the competition had been rigged.{{sfn|Williams|1995|p=112a|ps=: \"... supporters of William Barre claimed that the conditions had been transgressed ...\"}}\n\nThe fourth design had been submitted by the firm Lanyon & Lynn, a partnership of [[Charles Lanyon]] and [[William Henry Lynn]] that lasted from the mid-1850s to 1860.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lanyon & Lynn |url=https://www.dia.ie/architects/view/3088/LANYON+%26+LYNN |website=Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940 |publisher=Irish Architectural Archive |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> The design showed a tower in the [[Scottish Baronial]] style that could be understood as a [[peel tower]] and a symbol of the landlord as a chivalrous protector of his tenants in times of danger. Such a tower was considered especially suitable for a Stewart as the [[House of Stuart|Stewarts or Stuarts]] ruled Scotland during the times when peel towers were erected.\n\nThe [[Frederick Temple Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 1st Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|5th Baron Dufferin and Claneboye]], a neighbour of the Londonderrys, had recently built [[Helen's Tower]], also in the Scottish Baronial style, on the next hill to the north of Scrabo: the new tower was to have more than double the height of theirs.\n\n[[File:Londonderry Memorial Tower (project) Watercolour.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A framed picture showing the tower |Artist' View of the Londonderry Memorial Tower,<ref name=pict>{{cite web |title=Londonderry Memorial Tower on Scrabo Hill |url=http://www.nationaltrustcollections.org.uk/object/1220367 |publisher=National Trust Collections |accessdate=29 July 2018}}</ref> believed to represent the original project by Lanyon & Lynn]]\n\nA gilt-framed picture of the Scrabo Tower, which seems to be a coloured-in wood engraving, is preserved at Mount Stewart. It gives an artist's view of the Londonderry Monument, showing three towers linked by two short stretches of crenellated wall.<ref name=pict /> The middle tower resembles the one built. The others are much smaller. Wood engravings similar to this picture have been published in the [[The Illustrated London News|Illustrated London News]]{{sfn|Illustrated London News|1857|p=299b|ps=: \"Memorial to the late Marquis of Londonderry, in course of Erection on Scrabo Hill, County Down, Ireland\"}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Memorial To The Late Marquis Of Londonderry, In Course Of Erection On Scrabo Hill, County Down, Ireland (picture from Dublin Libraries) |work=The Illustrated London News |issue=March 28, 1857 |page=299 |url=http://www.dublincity.ie/image/libraries/iln-028-scrabo}}</ref> and the [[Dublin Builder]]. It seems that these pictures represent the original project before simplification to cut cost. Lynn's obituary in the [[Irish Builder]] attributes the design to Lynn.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Obituary: HW Lynn |journal=The Irish Builder and Engineer |volume=57 |issue=25 September 1915 |page=431}} cited in {{cite web |title=Co. Down, Scrabo Hill, Londonderry Monument |url=https://www.dia.ie/works/view/872/building/CO.+DOWN%2C+SCRABO+HILL%2C+LONDONDERRY+MONUMENT |website=Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940 |publisher=Irish Architectural Archive |accessdate=17 July 2018 |quote=But obituary of Lynn in IB 57, 25 Sep 1915, 431, says it was designed by Lynn}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation stone was laid on 27 February 1857 by [[Sir Robert Bateson, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert Bateson]] and blessed by the Church of Ireland bishop of the diocese on demand by [[William Sharman Crawford]], chairman of the Building Committee, in a ceremony attended by the 4th Marquess, his wife, many members of the gentry, and a crowd of residents and tenants.{{sfn|Illustrated London News|1857|p=300}} The Dowager Marchioness, the 4th Marquess's stepmother, was conspicuously absent.\n\nThe construction generally followed the accepted plans, but the tower's height was shortened and its form was simplified by omitting the crenellated walls and the wing towers. Work ceased in 1859 after the cost had risen to \u00a33010.{{sfn|McCavery|1994|p=140c|ps=: \"In the end, however, the 135 feet high monument actually cost \u00a33,010.\"}} The contractor was ruined, and the interior was left unfinished. In 1865 the Dublin Builder somewhat belatedly published an article about the tower. The author's purpose seems to have been to defend Lanyon and the Londonderrys against accusations of having rigged the competition. This article overstates the tower's height as 195&nbsp;feet instead of 135 and understates the cost of the tower as \u00a32300 instead of \u00a33010.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124c|ps=: \"The cost was about 2,300, and the total height 195&nbsp;feet.\"}} It also exaggerates the contribution made by the tenants to the point of making us believe that the tower was exclusively financed by the tenants.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124d|ps=: \"It has been erected by the tenantry of the late Marquis of Londonderry, ...\"}}\n\nThe tower is massive and imposing, symbolizing landlord power.{{sfn|McCavery|1994|p=141|ps=: \" \"... if the tower is a symbol of anything, it is surely a symbol of landlord power.\"}} This effect was the main purpose according to the article in the Dublin Builder.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124h|ps=: \"... size and mass were the chief objects to be attained at a comparably small cost ...\"}} In later appreciations it is found \"more curious than beautiful\"{{sfn|Williams|1995|p=112|ps=: \"more curious than beautiful\"}} and \"one of the finest examples of 19th century folly towers\".{{sfn|Howley|1993|p=[https://archive.org/details/folliesgardenbui00howl/page/54 54, right column, line 5]|ps=: \"Two of the finest examples of nineteenth-century folly towers are found standing within a few miles from each other, at Scrabo and Clandeboye in north Co. Down.\"}}\n\n===Later events===\nAfter the tower's completion in 1859, William McKay, a foreman of the quarry, moved into the tower as caretaker. His family ran a tearoom in the tower until 1966<ref name=\"Orme\" /> despite the lack of water at the top of the hill. The tower and the grounds on which it stands were then acquired by the state. In 1977, the tower was listed as a [[list of Grade B+ listed buildings in County Down|Grade B+ historic building]].{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031b]|ps=: \"Survey 2: B+\"}} The Department of Environment spent \u00a320,000 on the tower in 1992, repairing windows, repointing the masonry, adding lightning protection and fitting in a wooden floor between the second and third floor, which had been omitted in 1859 to cut costs.{{sfn|Brett|2002|p=272|ps=: \"Having fallen in considerable disrepair, it was taken into public ownership, and \u00a320,000 was spent on its restoration in 1992.\"}} The tower now stands in the Scrabo [[Country Park]], which is managed by the Northern Ireland Environment Agency (NIEA).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discovernorthernireland.com/Scrabo-Tower-and-Country-Park-Newtownards-P2886 |title=Scrabo Tower and Country Park |publisher=Northern Ireland Tourist Board |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> In 2014, the NIEA announced that water ingress had damaged the electricity supply, and citing safety concerns, closed the tower to visitors.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.u.tv/News/Scrabo-Tower-shut-for-foreseeable-future/d6d99a3e-f9de-493a-a2f8-b89a4766c47a |publisher=UTV News |title=Scrabo Tower shut for foreseeable future |date=22 April 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-27114225 | publisher=BBC News| title=Scrabo Tower: County Down monument closed to the public |date=22 April 2014 }}</ref>\nBy 2015, the tower opened occasionally,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discovernorthernireland.com/Scrabo-Tower-for-EHOD-2015-Newtownards-P52395 |publisher=Northern Ireland Tourist Board |accessdate=13 September 2015 |title=Scrabo Tower - European Heritage Open Day (EHOD) 2015 Cultural Event - 12-13 September}}</ref>\nand in 2017 it was fully reopened to the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-40525496|publisher=BBC|title=Scrabo Tower reopens to the public |date=7 July 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Scrabo_Tower_near_Newtownards_(6)_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1398819.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of the tower's roofs |The tower's roofs in 2009. Note the lapped stone roofs. The frame added near the top carries two [[aircraft warning light]]s.{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031c]|ps=: \"The large central \u2018roof\u2019 tower has a beacon for aircraft to the pinnacle of its conical roof.\"]]\n\nThe tower's style is called [[Scottish baronial architecture|Scottish Baronial]] by most recent authors.{{sfn|Williams|1995|p=112b|ps=: \"The Scrabo memorial is a multi-storied Scottish baronial tower ...\"}}{{sfn|Jones|1974|p=429}}: \"... mysteriously designed in the Scottish baronial style ...\" The article in the Illustrated London News of 1857 says \"... in the style of a Scottish chateau, ...\",<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEIllustrated London News1857299b\"/>{{sfn|Illustrated London News|1857|p=299b|ps=: \"Memorial to the late Marquis of Londonderry, in course of Erection on Scrabo Hill, County Down, Ireland\"}} whereas the article in the Dublin Builder of 1865 calls it \"Scotch baronial\".{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124e|ps=: \"... Scotch baronial ...\"}} Its height is {{convert|135|ft}}<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEMcCavery1994140c\"/> as can be confirmed by measuring the scaled elevation drawing in Howley (1993).{{sfn|Howley|1993|p=[https://archive.org/details/folliesgardenbui00howl/page/57 57, right column, Figure 86]|ps=: \"86. Scrabo Tower: elevation\"}} However, heights of 125&nbsp;feet<ref name=Orme /> and 195&nbsp;feet<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEDublin Builder1865124c\"/> have been given.\n\nThe tower consists of a base, a main body and a crenellated and turreted roof. The base contains the ground floor. It has [[Batter (walls)|battered]] (sloped) outer surfaces. The main body has vertical walls. The limit between the base and the main body is marked by a sandstone [[belt course]]. The base and the main body are square in plan and comprise a round [[staircase tower|stair tower]] that projects from the southeast corner. The tower's square part is surmounted by a short setback cylindrical storey that is covered with a steep conical roof. The transition from square to round is achieved by a platform decorated with four corner turrets linked by [[Machicolation|machicolated]] [[battlements]]. The turrets are round and also wear steep conical roofs. The five roofs are entirely built in lapped stone courses. The southeastern turret serves as cap-house over the stairs giving access to the parapet walk (or [[chemin de ronde]]). The other three turrets are smaller and sit on corbelled bases. Each of these bases consists of a pile of five roll-moulded corbel courses. A chimney stack is attached to the inner side of the northwestern turret.{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031d]|ps=: \"Exterior Description And Setting\"}}\n\nThe tower's entrance door is on the north face. It is accessed by a short outer stair. The door is surmounted by a commemorative plaque in a bluish black stone, probably slate. The inscription dedicates the monument to the 3rd Marquess. Following his change of surname,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/17480/page/906 ...may, in compliance with the provisions of the last will and testament of the said Sir Henry Vane, Bart. from henceforth continue respectively to use the surname of Vane only, ...</ref> he is called Vane rather than Stewart. The [[post-nominal]] KG stands for [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Garter]]. The \"& c\" should be read \"et cetera\" and means that the marquess's many lesser post-nominals were omitted.\n\n<div style=\"background: gainsboro; border: thin solid gray; float: left; font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: smaller; margin: 6px 16px 6px 0;  padding: 6px 16px; text-align: center;\">\nERECTED<br />\nIN MEMORY OF<br />\nCHARLES WILLIAM VANE<br />\n3<sup><span><small style=\"font-family: sans-serif\">RD</small></span></sup> MARQUIS OF LONDONDERRY<br />\nKG & c<br />\nBY HIS TENANTRY AND FRIENDS<br />\n<span style=\"font-family: sans-serif\"><small>\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014<br />\nFAME BELONGS TO HISTORY, REMEMBRANCE TO US</small></span><br />\n1857\n</div>\n\n[[File:CIMG1476 ScraboPlaque.JPG|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of the inscription and relief above the tower's entrance |Inscription surmounted by a relief showing Londonderry coronet, crests & motto]]\n\nAbove the plaque is a recess filled with a relief in white limestone or marble showing the coronet, two crests (dragon and sword arm), and the motto of the [[Marquess of Londonderry|marquesses of Londonderry]]. The relief is deeply undercut under the coronet and behind the dragon's wing. The coronet is decorated with three leaves and two balls as befits a marquess. The dragon crest represents the Stewart family. The arm (more precisely \"cubit\") with the hand in a gauntlet holding a sword represents the Vane family. The scroll below the coronet and the crests shows the motto (in Latin), which reads: METUENDA COROLLA DRACONIS (the dragon's crest is to be feared).\n\nThe tower should have had eight levels according to the placement of its windows on the wood engraving: the ground floor in the base, six floors in the main body and one in the setback masonry cylinder that occupies the centre of the platform and carries the main roof. When work stopped in 1859, only the ground floor and the first floor had floors and ceilings. All the space in the tower above the first floor's ceiling right up into the cone of the main roof was left empty. The ground floor was the caretaker's apartment. The first floor was planned as an armoury as would be required in a peel tower but was never equipped and used as such.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124f}} This armoury is covered with a brick [[groin vault]], which is the reason why the spacing between the armoury's windows and those of the second floor is wider than those between the other levels in the main body. A proper second floor was created later by inserting a wooden floor as part of the repairs and the upgrading done by the Department of Environment. This second floor was thus gained on the remaining undivided space.\n\nTwo types of stone were used in the tower: whitish to pinkish [[Triassic]] sandstone{{sfn|Hull|1872|pp=269\u2013270|ps=: \"At Scrabo Hill ... sandstone belonging to the upper division of the Trias ... are to be found;\"}} and dark-grey [[dolerite]]. The sandstone, more suitable for fine carvings, was used for [[quoins]], window dressings, stairs, corbels, copings and roofs, as well as for courses that mark limits: the moulding between the base and the main body and the one that separates the stair tower from the cap-house above it. The dolerite is described as [[whinstone]] or as basalt in various sources.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124g\ng|ps=: \"... a green whinstone ...\"}}{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031e]|ps=: \"... constructed in random basalt rubble ...\"}} This material is harder and more resistant to weathering than the sandstone but difficult to work. It was cut into blocks of variable size and laid in frequently interrupted courses. The outer surfaces of these blocks were left in rough [[rustication (architecture)|rustication]] with many blocks quite prominent.\n\n[[File:Scrobo_Tower,_from_across_Strangford_Lough.JPG|thumbnail|alt=Photograph on Scrabo Hill with tower seen from far |The tower, seen from the other side of Strangford Lough]]\n\n==Surroundings and view==\nScrabo Hill rises to a height of {{convert|540|ft}} above mean sea level. The viewing platform or parapet walk of the tower, reached by climbing 122 steps, provides views over [[Strangford Lough]] and its islands, as well as the towns of Newtownards and [[Comber]]. As the area to the south and southwest of Scrabo Hill is part of the Ulster [[Drumlin]] Belt, this glacial landform can be very well observed from the tower.\n\nOn clear days Helen's Tower in the north, the [[Copeland Islands]] with their lighthouse and the Scottish coast ([[Mull of Kintyre]], [[Ailsa Craig]] and [[Rhins of Galloway]])<ref name=Orme /> beyond the [[North Channel (Great Britain and Ireland)|North Channel]] in the northeast, the [[Isle of Man]] in the southeast, the [[Mourne Mountains]] in the south, as well as [[Divis]] Mountain and [[Cavehill|Cave Hill]] over Belfast in the west can be seen.\n\nScrabo Country Park, in which the tower stands, includes parts of the top and the eastern and southern slopes of Scrabo Hill as well as Killynether Wood.<ref>{{cite web |last=Department of Environment |title=Scrabo Landscape Character Assessment (LCA 101) |url=https://www.daera-ni.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/doe/environment-land-information-NI-landscape-character-assessment-scrabo-2006.pdf |publisher=Department of Environment |accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> The eastern part of the hill is of geological interest because outcrops in the South Quarry reveal contacts between sediments (sandstone) and locally cross-cutting [[sill (geology)|sills]] of intrusive rocks (dolerite). This eastern part, which includes the site of the tower, has been declared an Area of Special Scientific Interest (ASSI).<ref>{{cite web |title=Declaration of Area of Special Scientific Interest at Scrabo Co. Down (ASSI-91) |url=https://www.daera-ni.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/doe/scrabo-citation-documents-map.pdf |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Much of the plateau on top of the hill to the west of the tower is occupied by Scrabo Golf Course.\n\n==In fiction==\nThe ''[[The Enchanted Duplicator|Enchanted Duplicator]]'', a story by the Northern Irish writers [[Walt Willis]] and [[Bob Shaw]], features the Tower of Trufandom (true fandom), which was inspired by Scrabo Tower.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fanac.org/fanzines/Enchanted_Duplicator/Enchanted-00.html |title=The Enchanted Duplicator |last=Willis |first=Walt |last2=Shaw |first2=Bob |date=February 1954 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=25 February 2009 |quote=This, he knew, must be the Tower of Trufandom}}</ref>\n[[Patrick Nielsen Hayden]] and his wife Teresa tell in an article published in Number 37 of the Hyphen, a periodic edited by Walt Willis, how they visited Scrabo Tower with Walt Willis in a literary pilgrimage.{{sfn|Nielsen Hayden|Nielsen Hayden|1987|p=37|ps=: \"The tower itself is tall and square, built of rough brown stone blocks, and pretty much looks like everybody's idea of what a generic tower should be, which is a virtue in allegorical objects.\"}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{citation|last=Brett |first=Charles Edward Bainbridge |author-link=Charles Brett |date=2002 |title=Buildings of North County Down |publisher=Ulster Architectural Heritage Society |publication-place=Belfast |isbn=978-0900457579}}\n*{{citation|author=Dublin Builder |date=15 May 1865 |title=The Londonderry Monument, Scraboh Hill, Co Down |journal=The Dublin Builder |volume=vii |issue=130 |page=124 |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/search/results/1865-05-15?NewspaperTitle=The%2BDublin%2BBuilder&IssueId=BL%2F0000895%2F18650515%2F&County=Dublin%2C%20Republic%20of%20Ireland |url-access=subscription |accessdate=10 December 2019}}\n*{{citation|title=Historic Building Details - HB Ref No: HB24/11/031 |publisher=Department for Communities |location=Belfast |url=https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 |access-date=1 March 2019 |ref=CITEREFHistoric Building Details}}\n*{{citation|last=Howley |first=James |date=1993 |title=The Follies and Garden Buildings of Ireland |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven, Connecticut |isbn=0-300-10225-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/folliesgardenbui00howl |url-access=registration}}\n*{{citation|last=Hull |first=Edward |date=1872 |title=The Building and Ornamental Stones of Great Britain and Foreign Countries |publisher=Macmillan & Co. |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/atreatiseonbuil04hullgoog}}\n*{{citation|last=Hyde |first=Harford Montgomery |date=1979 |title=The Londonderrys - A Family Portrait |publisher=Hamish Hamilton |publication-place=London |isbn=0241101530 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wGBmAAAAMAAJ}}\n*{{citation|author=Illustrated London News |date=1857 |title=Memorial To The Late Marquis Of Londonderry, In Course Of Erection On Scrabo Hill, County Down, Ireland |journal=The Illustrated London News |issue=March 28, 1857 |page=299 |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001578/18570328/081/0021 |url-access=subscription}}\n*{{citation|last=Jones |first=Barbara Mildred |date=1974 |title=Follies and Grottoes |edition=2nd, heavily revised and enlarged |publisher=Constable & Co. |publication-place=London |isbn=978-0094593503 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JYxsYXsKwnQC}} - Scrabo seems not to be mentioned in the 1st edition, published in 1953.\n*{{citation|last=Lloyd |first=E. M. |editor-last=Matthew |editor-first=Colin |editor-link=Colin Matthew |editor2-last=Harrison |editor2-first=Brian |editor2-link=Brian Harrison (historian) |date=2004 |title=Vane, Charles William, third marquess of Londonderry (1778\u20131854) |encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=56 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |publication-place=New York |pages=95\u201398 |isbn=0-19-861406-3 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198614063/page/95 |url-access=registration}}\n*{{citation|last=McCavery |first=Trevor |date=1994 |title=Newtown - A history of Newtownards |publisher=The White Row Press |publication-place=Belfast |isbn=9781870132701}}\n*{{citation|last=McKay |first=Patrick |date=2007 |title=A Dictionary of Ulster Place-Names |edition=2nd |publisher=Cl\u00f3 Ollscoil na Banr\u00edona |publication-place=Belfast |isbn=0-85389-896-0}}\n*{{citation|last=Nielsen Hayden |first=Patrick James |last2=Nielsen Hayden |first2=Teresa |date=August 1987 |title=Aspects and Inclinations |journal=Hyphen |issue=37 |url=http://www.efanzines.com/Hyphen/Hyphen37/index.htm#37 |accessdate=1 May 2008}}\n*{{citation |last=Pointon |first=Graham E. |date=1990 |title=BBC Pronouncing Dictionary of British Names |publisher=Oxford University Press |publication-place=Oxford |isbn=0-19-282745-6 |edition=2nd |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/bbcpronouncingdi00gepo}}\n*{{citation|last=Vane |first=Charles William |date=1828 |title=Narrative of the Peninsular War |publisher=Henry Colburn |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/narrativeofpenin00lond}}\n*{{citation|last=Williams |first=Jeremy |date=1995 |title=A Companion Guide to Architecture in Ireland 1837-1921 |publisher=Irish Academic Press |publication-place=Dublin |isbn=978-0716525134 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JChVAAAAMAAJ}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in County Down]]\n[[Category:Towers in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Newtownards]]\n[[Category:Grade B+ listed buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|19th century folly in Northern Ireland}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{infobox historic site\n|name=Scrabo Tower\n|image=CIMG1495 ScraboHorizView.JPG\n|alt=Photograph of the tower against a blue sky with white clouds\n|caption=Scrabo Tower, May 2007\n|locmapin=UK Northern Ireland\n|map_caption=Location in Northern Ireland\n|coordinates={{coord|54.58010|-5.7155|type:landmark_scale:5000|display=title,inline}}\n|built=1857-1859\n|architect=Lanyon & Lynn\n|designation1=Grade B+ listed building\n|designation1_date=1977\n|designation1_number=HB24/11/031\n}}\n'''Scrabo Tower''' is a {{convert|135|ft}} high 19th-century lookout tower or folly that stands on Scrabo Hill near [[Newtownards]] in [[County Down]], [[Northern Ireland]]. It provides wide views and is a landmark that can be seen from afar. It was built as a memorial to [[Charles Vane, 3rd Marquess of Londonderry]] and was originally known as the '''Londonderry Monument'''. Its architectural style is [[Scottish baronial architecture#Scottish Baronial Revival|Scottish Baronial Revival]].{{harv|Howley|1993}}\n\n== Name and location ==\nNowadays, the tower on Scrabo Hill is usually just called Scrabo Tower and is visited for its views and surroundings. However, its original name was Londonderry Monument or Memorial. That name referred to the [[Marquess of Londonderry|Marquesses of Londonderry]] and only indirectly to the town or county of that name, which is {{convert|87|miles|km}} away. The marquesses owned much ground around the hill. The hill and tower rise over the town of [[Newtownards]], {{convert|10|mi|km}} east of Belfast. As the tower dominates the town, it is often used as an emblem for Newtownards. The tower is built on the site of a prehistoric hill fort.{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031a]|ps=: \"During the Bronze Age the summit of Scrabo Hill was the site of a considerable settlement, enclosed within an oval hill fort.\"}}{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124a|ps=: \"The excavations for the foundations disclosed a vast quantity of wild boar tusks and bones, suggesting that the elevated position had been formerly the scene of Druidical sacrifices or of pre-historic pic-nics.\"}} Scrabo is pronounced {{IPAc-en|'|s|k|r|\u00e6|b|ou}} according to the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC){{sfn|Pointon|1990|p=[https://archive.org/details/bbcpronouncingdi00gepo/page/217 217] |ps=: \"skr\u00e6bo\u028a\"}} or {{IPA-sco|\u02c8skr\u0251\u02d0bo|}} according to the pronunciation heard on the ''[[Placenames Database of Ireland]]'' website.<ref name=DCU>{{cite web |url=https://www.logainm.ie/en/1413295 |title=The Placenames Database of Ireland |publisher=Dublin City University |accessdate=1 September 2018}}</ref> The pronunciation of the final vowel as the pure sound [o] rather than the diphthong [ou] is also attested by the spelling variation Scraboh.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124b|ps=: \"The Londonderry Monument, Scraboh Hill, Co Down\"}}\n\nTwo etymologies are proposed for Scrabo. The first derives the name from Irish ''screabach'' meaning \"rough stony land\".{{sfn|McKay|2007|p=129}} Screabach is also the Irish name of the Scrabo townland in which the hill lies.<ref name=DCU /> The second derives the name from Irish ''scraith b\u00f3'', which means \"sward of the cow\",<ref>[https://www.logainm.ie/en/ Placenames Database of Ireland]. Search for Scrabo. Then find the right archival document by clicking the Open Scanned Records Button. Note 'scraith b\u00f3' and 'sward of the cow'.</ref> \"cow pasture\",<ref name=Orme>{{cite web |last=Orme |first=Debby |url=http://scrabotower.com/scrabo-tower.html |title=The History of Scrabo Tower - Guardian of the North Down coast |accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> or \"sod of the cow\",{{sfn|Jones|1974|p=429}} as ''scraith'' means sward, sod or turf, whereas ''b\u00f3'' means cow. This derivation explains the final \"o\" of Scrabo.\n\n==History==\n===Origins===\nThe tower commemorates the [[Charles Vane, 3rd Marquess of Londonderry|3rd Marquess of Londonderry]], who was born Charles William Stewart in 1788. He fought in the Napoleonic Wars.{{sfn|Vane |1828}} He became married twice first Catherine Bligh and then [[Frances Vane, Marchioness of Londonderry|Frances Anne Vane]]. At his second wife was a rich heiress and the marriage contract obliged him to change his surname to hers, which explains why he was first called Stewart and later Vane. He succeeded his half-brother [[Viscount Castlereagh]] as marquess in 1822 and became owner of the family estate in County Down. The estate's great house, [[Mount Stewart]], became his Irish residence but after his second marriage he lived mostly in England.\n\nIn 1854, when the 3rd Marquess died, his eldest son, [[Frederick Stewart, 4th Marquess of Londonderry]], and his widow, the dowager marchioness, decided to build him a monument. As these two were not at good terms, each conceived and pushed his or her own project. Two monuments resulted: the Irish tower discussed here and an equestrian statue in Durham, England.{{sfn|Lloyd|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198614063/page/98 98]|ps=: \"an equestrian statue by him by Gaetano Monti was unveiled in the market-place at Durham by Disraeli on 2 December 1861.\"}}\n\nA committee was formed in Newtownards to raise funds by subscription for an Irish monument. The local gentry and the late marquess's friends, among which [[Napoleon III]] of France, donated most of the money, with some of the tenants also contributing.{{sfn|McCavery|1994|p=140a|ps=: \"Two thirds of the cost was raised by 98 individuals (the list was headed by the Emperor Napoleon III of France), most of whom were fellow gentry from Antrim and Down, and personal friends of the Marquess.\"}} Altogether 730 people subscribed.{{sfn|Illustrated London News|1857|p=299a|ps=: \"There was also placed in the jar a list of the subscribers' names, 730 of them all;\"}} The person behind these efforts was his eldest son [[Frederick Stewart, 4th Marquess of Londonderry]].{{sfn|Hyde|1979|p=50|ps=: \"At the same time her husband constructed the great tower on Scrabo Hill overlooking the town in his father's memory.\"}}\n\nThe funds raised allowed for a budget of \u00a32000. At first, the monument was to be built in Newtownards, but it was later shifted to Scrabo Hill where it could be seen from Mount Stewart and where suitable building stone was quarried. In December 1855 the committee decided to hold a design competition.{{sfn|McCavery|1994|p=140b|ps=: \"In 1855, it was decided that the memorial should be erected on Scrabo, and that the design should be subject of a competition with the cost of the work not to exceed \u00a32,000.\"}} The deadline was 1 February 1856.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archiseek.com/2011/1857-scrabo-tower-newtownards-co-down/#.U1k7q_ldVws |publisher=Archiseek |title=1857 \u2013 Scrabo Tower, Newtownards, Co. Down |quote=The architects designs were to be received before February 1, 1856 }}</ref> Four entries were considered: an obelisk and three towers. The first prize went to the obelisk, which was submitted by [[W. J. Barre|William Joseph Barre]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Co. Down, Scrabo Hill, Londonderry Monument |url=https://www.dia.ie/works/view/872/building/CO.+DOWN%2C+SCRABO+HILL%2C+LONDONDERRY+MONUMENT |website=Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940 |publisher=Irish Architectural Archive |accessdate=17 July 2018 |quote=Placed 1st in competition}}</ref> However, the obelisk came to nothing and indeed none of the first three projects was executed. When the committee called for tenders from building contractors, all the submissions for the three best-rated entries exceeded the budget and were therefore rejected. Finally, a tender by Hugh Dixon from Newtownards for the fourth project was accepted.<ref>{{cite web |title=Co. Down, Scrabo Hill, Londonderry Monument |url=https://www.dia.ie/works/view/872/building/CO.+DOWN%2C+SCRABO+HILL%2C+LONDONDERRY+MONUMENT |website=Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940 |publisher=Irish Architectural Archive |accessdate=17 July 2018 |quote=Contractor: Hugh Dixon, Newtownards}}</ref> However, supporters of William Barre claimed that the competition had been rigged.{{sfn|Williams|1995|p=112a|ps=: \"... supporters of William Barre claimed that the conditions had been transgressed ...\"}}\n\nThe fourth design had been submitted by the firm Lanyon & Lynn, a partnership of [[Charles Lanyon]] and [[William Henry Lynn]] that lasted from the mid-1850s to 1860.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lanyon & Lynn |url=https://www.dia.ie/architects/view/3088/LANYON+%26+LYNN |website=Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940 |publisher=Irish Architectural Archive |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> The design showed a tower in the [[Scottish Baronial]] style that could be understood as a [[peel tower]] and a symbol of the landlord as a chivalrous protector of his tenants in times of danger. Such a tower was considered especially suitable for a Stewart as the [[House of Stuart|Stewarts or Stuarts]] ruled Scotland during the times when peel towers were erected.\n\nThe [[Frederick Temple Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 1st Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|5th Baron Dufferin and Claneboye]], a neighbour of the Londonderrys, had recently built [[Helen's Tower]], also in the Scottish Baronial style, on the next hill to the north of Scrabo: the new tower was to have more than double the height of theirs.\n\n[[File:Londonderry Memorial Tower (project) Watercolour.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A framed picture showing the tower |Artist' View of the Londonderry Memorial Tower,<ref name=pict>{{cite web |title=Londonderry Memorial Tower on Scrabo Hill |url=http://www.nationaltrustcollections.org.uk/object/1220367 |publisher=National Trust Collections |accessdate=29 July 2018}}</ref> believed to represent the original project by Lanyon & Lynn]]\n\nA gilt-framed picture of the Scrabo Tower, which seems to be a coloured-in wood engraving, is preserved at Mount Stewart. It gives an artist's view of the Londonderry Monument, showing three towers linked by two short stretches of crenellated wall.<ref name=pict /> The middle tower resembles the one built. The others are much smaller. Wood engravings similar to this picture have been published in the [[The Illustrated London News|Illustrated London News]]{{sfn|Illustrated London News|1857|p=299b|ps=: \"Memorial to the late Marquis of Londonderry, in course of Erection on Scrabo Hill, County Down, Ireland\"}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Memorial To The Late Marquis Of Londonderry, In Course Of Erection On Scrabo Hill, County Down, Ireland (picture from Dublin Libraries) |work=The Illustrated London News |issue=March 28, 1857 |page=299 |url=http://www.dublincity.ie/image/libraries/iln-028-scrabo}}</ref> and the [[Dublin Builder]]. It seems that these pictures represent the original project before simplification to cut cost. Lynn's obituary in the [[Irish Builder]] attributes the design to Lynn.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Obituary: HW Lynn |journal=The Irish Builder and Engineer |volume=57 |issue=25 September 1915 |page=431}} cited in {{cite web |title=Co. Down, Scrabo Hill, Londonderry Monument |url=https://www.dia.ie/works/view/872/building/CO.+DOWN%2C+SCRABO+HILL%2C+LONDONDERRY+MONUMENT |website=Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940 |publisher=Irish Architectural Archive |accessdate=17 July 2018 |quote=But obituary of Lynn in IB 57, 25 Sep 1915, 431, says it was designed by Lynn}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation stone was laid on 27 February 1857 by [[Sir Robert Bateson, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert Bateson]] and blessed by the Church of Ireland bishop of the diocese on demand by [[William Sharman Crawford]], chairman of the Building Committee, in a ceremony attended by the 4th Marquess, his wife, many members of the gentry, and a crowd of residents and tenants.{{sfn|Illustrated London News|1857|p=300}} The Dowager Marchioness, the 4th Marquess's stepmother, was conspicuously absent.\n\nThe construction generally followed the accepted plans, but the tower's height was shortened and its form was simplified by omitting the crenellated walls and the wing towers. Work ceased in 1859 after the cost had risen to \u00a33010.{{sfn|McCavery|1994|p=140c|ps=: \"In the end, however, the 135 feet high monument actually cost \u00a33,010.\"}} The contractor was ruined, and the interior was left unfinished. In 1865 the Dublin Builder somewhat belatedly published an article about the tower. The author's purpose seems to have been to defend Lanyon and the Londonderrys against accusations of having rigged the competition. This article overstates the tower's height as 195&nbsp;feet instead of 135 and understates the cost of the tower as \u00a32300 instead of \u00a33010.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124c|ps=: \"The cost was about 2,300, and the total height 195&nbsp;feet.\"}} It also exaggerates the contribution made by the tenants to the point of making us believe that the tower was exclusively financed by the tenants.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124d|ps=: \"It has been erected by the tenantry of the late Marquis of Londonderry, ...\"}}\n\nThe tower is massive and imposing, symbolizing landlord power.{{sfn|McCavery|1994|p=141|ps=: \" \"... if the tower is a symbol of anything, it is surely a symbol of landlord power.\"}} This effect was the main purpose according to the article in the Dublin Builder.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124h|ps=: \"... size and mass were the chief objects to be attained at a comparably small cost ...\"}} In later appreciations it is found \"more curious than beautiful\"{{sfn|Williams|1995|p=112|ps=: \"more curious than beautiful\"}} and \"one of the finest examples of 19th century folly towers\".{{sfn|Howley|1993|p=[https://archive.org/details/folliesgardenbui00howl/page/54 54, right column, line 5]|ps=: \"Two of the finest examples of nineteenth-century folly towers are found standing within a few miles from each other, at Scrabo and Clandeboye in north Co. Down.\"}}\n\n===Later events===\nAfter the tower's completion in 1859, William McKay, a foreman of the quarry, moved into the tower as caretaker. His family ran a tearoom in the tower until 1966<ref name=\"Orme\" /> despite the lack of water at the top of the hill. The tower and the grounds on which it stands were then acquired by the state. In 1977, the tower was listed as a [[list of Grade B+ listed buildings in County Down|Grade B+ historic building]].{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031b]|ps=: \"Survey 2: B+\"}} The Department of Environment spent \u00a320,000 on the tower in 1992, repairing windows, repointing the masonry, adding lightning protection and fitting in a wooden floor between the second and third floor, which had been omitted in 1859 to cut costs.{{sfn|Brett|2002|p=272|ps=: \"Having fallen in considerable disrepair, it was taken into public ownership, and \u00a320,000 was spent on its restoration in 1992.\"}} The tower now stands in the Scrabo [[Country Park]], which is managed by the Northern Ireland Environment Agency (NIEA).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discovernorthernireland.com/Scrabo-Tower-and-Country-Park-Newtownards-P2886 |title=Scrabo Tower and Country Park |publisher=Northern Ireland Tourist Board |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> In 2014, the NIEA announced that water ingress had damaged the electricity supply, and citing safety concerns, closed the tower to visitors.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.u.tv/News/Scrabo-Tower-shut-for-foreseeable-future/d6d99a3e-f9de-493a-a2f8-b89a4766c47a |publisher=UTV News |title=Scrabo Tower shut for foreseeable future |date=22 April 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-27114225 | publisher=BBC News| title=Scrabo Tower: County Down monument closed to the public |date=22 April 2014 }}</ref>\nBy 2015, the tower opened occasionally,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discovernorthernireland.com/Scrabo-Tower-for-EHOD-2015-Newtownards-P52395 |publisher=Northern Ireland Tourist Board |accessdate=13 September 2015 |title=Scrabo Tower - European Heritage Open Day (EHOD) 2015 Cultural Event - 12-13 September}}</ref>\nand in 2017 it was fully reopened to the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-40525496|publisher=BBC|title=Scrabo Tower reopens to the public |date=7 July 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Scrabo_Tower_near_Newtownards_(6)_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1398819.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of the tower's roofs |The tower's roofs in 2009. Note the lapped stone roofs. The frame added near the top carries two [[aircraft warning light]]s.{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031c]|ps=: \"The large central \u2018roof\u2019 tower has a beacon for aircraft to the pinnacle of its conical roof.\"]]\n\nThe tower's style is called [[Scottish baronial architecture|Scottish Baronial]] by most recent authors.{{sfn|Williams|1995|p=112b|ps=: \"The Scrabo memorial is a multi-storied Scottish baronial tower ...\"}}{{sfn|Jones|1974|p=429}}: \"... mysteriously designed in the Scottish baronial style ...\" The article in the Illustrated London News of 1857 says \"... in the style of a Scottish chateau, ...\",<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEIllustrated London News1857299b\"/>{{sfn|Illustrated London News|1857|p=299b|ps=: \"Memorial to the late Marquis of Londonderry, in course of Erection on Scrabo Hill, County Down, Ireland\"}} whereas the article in the Dublin Builder of 1865 calls it \"Scotch baronial\".{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124e|ps=: \"... Scotch baronial ...\"}} Its height is {{convert|135|ft}}<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEMcCavery1994140c\"/> as can be confirmed by measuring the scaled elevation drawing in Howley (1993).{{sfn|Howley|1993|p=[https://archive.org/details/folliesgardenbui00howl/page/57 57, right column, Figure 86]|ps=: \"86. Scrabo Tower: elevation\"}} However, heights of 125&nbsp;feet<ref name=Orme /> and 195&nbsp;feet<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEDublin Builder1865124c\"/> have been given.\n\nThe tower consists of a base, a main body and a crenellated and turreted roof. The base contains the ground floor. It has [[Batter (walls)|battered]] (sloped) outer surfaces. The main body has vertical walls. The limit between the base and the main body is marked by a sandstone [[belt course]]. The base and the main body are square in plan and comprise a round [[staircase tower|stair tower]] that projects from the southeast corner. The tower's square part is surmounted by a short setback cylindrical storey that is covered with a steep conical roof. The transition from square to round is achieved by a platform decorated with four corner turrets linked by [[Machicolation|machicolated]] [[battlements]]. The turrets are round and also wear steep conical roofs. The five roofs are entirely built in lapped stone courses. The southeastern turret serves as cap-house over the stairs giving access to the parapet walk (or [[chemin de ronde]]). The other three turrets are smaller and sit on corbelled bases. Each of these bases consists of a pile of five roll-moulded corbel courses. A chimney stack is attached to the inner side of the northwestern turret.{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031d]|ps=: \"Exterior Description And Setting\"}}\n\nThe tower's entrance door is on the north face. It is accessed by a short outer stair. The door is surmounted by a commemorative plaque in a bluish black stone, probably slate. The inscription dedicates the monument to the 3rd Marquess. Following his change of surname,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/17480/page/906 ...may, in compliance with the provisions of the last will and testament of the said Sir Henry Vane, Bart. from henceforth continue respectively to use the surname of Vane only, ...</ref> he is called Vane rather than Stewart. The [[post-nominal]] KG stands for [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Garter]]. The \"& c\" should be read \"et cetera\" and means that the marquess's many lesser post-nominals were omitted.\n\n<div style=\"background: gainsboro; border: thin solid gray; float: left; font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: smaller; margin: 6px 16px 6px 0;  padding: 6px 16px; text-align: center;\">\nERECTED<br />\nIN MEMORY OF<br />\nCHARLES WILLIAM VANE<br />\n3<sup><span><small style=\"font-family: sans-serif\">RD</small></span></sup> MARQUIS OF LONDONDERRY<br />\nKG & c<br />\nBY HIS TENANTRY AND FRIENDS<br />\n<span style=\"font-family: sans-serif\"><small>\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014<br />\nFAME BELONGS TO HISTORY, REMEMBRANCE TO US</small></span><br />\n1857\n</div>\n\n[[File:CIMG1476 ScraboPlaque.JPG|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of the inscription and relief above the tower's entrance |Inscription surmounted by a relief showing Londonderry coronet, crests & motto]]\n\nAbove the plaque is a recess filled with a relief in white limestone or marble showing the coronet, two crests (dragon and sword arm), and the motto of the [[Marquess of Londonderry|marquesses of Londonderry]]. The relief is deeply undercut under the coronet and behind the dragon's wing. The coronet is decorated with three leaves and two balls as befits a marquess. The dragon crest represents the Stewart family. The arm (more precisely \"cubit\") with the hand in a gauntlet holding a sword represents the Vane family. The scroll below the coronet and the crests shows the motto (in Latin), which reads: METUENDA COROLLA DRACONIS (the dragon's crest is to be feared).\n\nThe tower should have had eight levels according to the placement of its windows on the wood engraving: the ground floor in the base, six floors in the main body and one in the setback masonry cylinder that occupies the centre of the platform and carries the main roof. When work stopped in 1859, only the ground floor and the first floor had floors and ceilings. All the space in the tower above the first floor's ceiling right up into the cone of the main roof was left empty. The ground floor was the caretaker's apartment. The first floor was planned as an armoury as would be required in a peel tower but was never equipped and used as such.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124f}} This armoury is covered with a brick [[groin vault]], which is the reason why the spacing between the armoury's windows and those of the second floor is wider than those between the other levels in the main body. A proper second floor was created later by inserting a wooden floor as part of the repairs and the upgrading done by the Department of Environment. This second floor was thus gained on the remaining undivided space.\n\nTwo types of stone were used in the tower: whitish to pinkish [[Triassic]] sandstone{{sfn|Hull|1872|pp=269\u2013270|ps=: \"At Scrabo Hill ... sandstone belonging to the upper division of the Trias ... are to be found;\"}} and dark-grey [[dolerite]]. The sandstone, more suitable for fine carvings, was used for [[quoins]], window dressings, stairs, corbels, copings and roofs, as well as for courses that mark limits: the moulding between the base and the main body and the one that separates the stair tower from the cap-house above it. The dolerite is described as [[whinstone]] or as basalt in various sources.{{sfn|Dublin Builder|1865|p=124g\ng|ps=: \"... a green whinstone ...\"}}{{sfn|Historic Building Details|loc=[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 Historic Building Details HB Ref No: HB24/11/031e]|ps=: \"... constructed in random basalt rubble ...\"}} This material is harder and more resistant to weathering than the sandstone but difficult to work. It was cut into blocks of variable size and laid in frequently interrupted courses. The outer surfaces of these blocks were left in rough [[rustication (architecture)|rustication]] with many blocks quite prominent.\n\n[[File:Scrobo_Tower,_from_across_Strangford_Lough.JPG|thumbnail|alt=Photograph on Scrabo Hill with tower seen from far |The tower, seen from the other side of Strangford Lough]]\n\n==Surroundings and view==\nScrabo Hill rises to a height of {{convert|540|ft}} above mean sea level. The viewing platform or parapet walk of the tower, reached by climbing 122 steps, provides views over [[Strangford Lough]] and its islands, as well as the towns of Newtownards and [[Comber]]. As the area to the south and southwest of Scrabo Hill is part of the Ulster [[Drumlin]] Belt, this glacial landform can be very well observed from the tower.\n\nOn clear days Helen's Tower in the north, the [[Copeland Islands]] with their lighthouse and the Scottish coast ([[Mull of Kintyre]], [[Ailsa Craig]] and [[Rhins of Galloway]])<ref name=Orme /> beyond the [[North Channel (Great Britain and Ireland)|North Channel]] in the northeast, the [[Isle of Man]] in the southeast, the [[Mourne Mountains]] in the south, as well as [[Divis]] Mountain and [[Cavehill|Cave Hill]] over Belfast in the west can be seen.\n\nScrabo Country Park, in which the tower stands, includes parts of the top and the eastern and southern slopes of Scrabo Hill as well as Killynether Wood.<ref>{{cite web |last=Department of Environment |title=Scrabo Landscape Character Assessment (LCA 101) |url=https://www.daera-ni.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/doe/environment-land-information-NI-landscape-character-assessment-scrabo-2006.pdf |publisher=Department of Environment |accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> The eastern part of the hill is of geological interest because outcrops in the South Quarry reveal contacts between sediments (sandstone) and locally cross-cutting [[sill (geology)|sills]] of intrusive rocks (dolerite). This eastern part, which includes the site of the tower, has been declared an Area of Special Scientific Interest (ASSI).<ref>{{cite web |title=Declaration of Area of Special Scientific Interest at Scrabo Co. Down (ASSI-91) |url=https://www.daera-ni.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/doe/scrabo-citation-documents-map.pdf |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Much of the plateau on top of the hill to the west of the tower is occupied by Scrabo Golf Course.\n\n==In fiction==\nThe ''[[The Enchanted Duplicator|Enchanted Duplicator]]'', a story by the Northern Irish writers [[Walt Willis]] and [[Bob Shaw]], features the Tower of Trufandom (true fandom), which was inspired by Scrabo Tower.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fanac.org/fanzines/Enchanted_Duplicator/Enchanted-00.html |title=The Enchanted Duplicator |last=Willis |first=Walt |last2=Shaw |first2=Bob |date=February 1954 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=25 February 2009 |quote=This, he knew, must be the Tower of Trufandom}}</ref>\n[[Patrick Nielsen Hayden]] and his wife Teresa tell in an article published in Number 37 of the Hyphen, a periodic edited by Walt Willis, how they visited Scrabo Tower with Walt Willis in a literary pilgrimage.{{sfn|Nielsen Hayden|Nielsen Hayden|1987|p=37|ps=: \"The tower itself is tall and square, built of rough brown stone blocks, and pretty much looks like everybody's idea of what a generic tower should be, which is a virtue in allegorical objects.\"}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{citation|last=Brett |first=Charles Edward Bainbridge |author-link=Charles Brett |date=2002 |title=Buildings of North County Down |publisher=Ulster Architectural Heritage Society |publication-place=Belfast |isbn=978-0900457579}}\n*{{citation|author=Dublin Builder |date=15 May 1865 |title=The Londonderry Monument, Scraboh Hill, Co Down |journal=The Dublin Builder |volume=vii |issue=130 |page=124 |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/search/results/1865-05-15?NewspaperTitle=The%2BDublin%2BBuilder&IssueId=BL%2F0000895%2F18650515%2F&County=Dublin%2C%20Republic%20of%20Ireland |url-access=subscription |accessdate=10 December 2019}}\n*{{citation|title=Historic Building Details - HB Ref No: HB24/11/031 |publisher=Department for Communities |location=Belfast |url=https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=6620 |access-date=1 March 2019 |ref=CITEREFHistoric Building Details}}\n*{{citation|last=Howley |first=James |date=1993 |title=The Follies and Garden Buildings of Ireland |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven, Connecticut |isbn=0-300-10225-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/folliesgardenbui00howl |url-access=registration}}\n*{{citation|last=Hull |first=Edward |date=1872 |title=The Building and Ornamental Stones of Great Britain and Foreign Countries |publisher=Macmillan & Co. |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/atreatiseonbuil04hullgoog}}\n*{{citation|last=Hyde |first=Harford Montgomery |date=1979 |title=The Londonderrys - A Family Portrait |publisher=Hamish Hamilton |publication-place=London |isbn=0241101530 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wGBmAAAAMAAJ}}\n*{{citation|author=Illustrated London News |date=1857 |title=Memorial To The Late Marquis Of Londonderry, In Course Of Erection On Scrabo Hill, County Down, Ireland |journal=The Illustrated London News |issue=March 28, 1857 |page=299 |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001578/18570328/081/0021 |url-access=subscription}}\n*{{citation|last=Jones |first=Barbara Mildred |date=1974 |title=Follies and Grottoes |edition=2nd, heavily revised and enlarged |publisher=Constable & Co. |publication-place=London |isbn=978-0094593503 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JYxsYXsKwnQC}} - Scrabo seems not to be mentioned in the 1st edition, published in 1953.\n*{{citation|last=Lloyd |first=E. M. |editor-last=Matthew |editor-first=Colin |editor-link=